var tipuesearch = {"pages": [{'title': 'About', 'text': '\n 這個倉儲位於\xa0 https://github.com/mdecourse/cmstemplate \xa0是一個能夠與 Github Pages, Gitlab Pages 以及 Heroku 結合的網際內容管理系統. \n', 'tags': '', 'url': 'About.html'}, {'title': 'Hint', 'text': '\n 是否了解如何設定 Github Pages? \n 是否了解如何設定 Gitlab Pages? \n 是否了解如何設定 Heroku? \n \n 作業一的目的: \n \n 閱讀與電腦軟硬體相關的英文資料, 藉以了解英文相關術語 \n 了解電腦與網路相關設定 \n 了解如何使用 Git, Github 與 CMSiMDE \n \n 作業二的目的: \n \n 實際了解 Python 程式在課程推動上的應用 \n 了解如何從網站超文件資料中擷取所要的資料 \n 使用 Kaggle 與近端 SciTE 開發 Python 程式 \n \n 作業三的目的: \n \n 著手利用 Python 解決各類問題 \n 利用 Python 修改 Solidworks 與 Inventor 零件尺寸 \n \n', 'tags': '', 'url': 'Hint.html'}, {'title': 'gitlab-ci.yml', 'text': '標題不能使用 .gitlab-ci.yml 因為轉為 content/.gitlab-ci.yml 時, 無法從 content/.github-ci.yml 呼叫. \n .gitlab-ci.yml 是在 Gitlab Pages 設定過程中將靜態網頁轉存並伺服的 continuout integration 設定檔案. \n pages:\n  stage: deploy\n  script:\n  - mkdir .public\n  - cp -r * .public\n  - mv .public public\n  artifacts:\n    paths:\n    - public\n  only:\n  - master\nvariables:\n  GIT_SUBMODULE_STRATEGY: recursive \n', 'tags': '', 'url': 'gitlab-ci.yml.html'}, {'title': 'CMSiMDE', 'text': '網際內容管理系統 \n Web-based Content Management System \n https://learnmech.com/ \n https://www.instructables.com/ \xa0\xa0 \n https://imechanica.org/ \xa0 \n https://info.traceparts.com/use-and-manage-3d-cad-models/download-free-cad-models/ \xa0 \n https://bookboon.com/en \xa0 \n \n', 'tags': '', 'url': 'CMSiMDE.html'}, {'title': 'CMSiMDE 程式架構', 'text': '動態網頁的主要檔案為 config/content.htm \n 當使用者在命令列中將目錄更換到 cmsimde, 然後以 python wsgi.py 執行 wsgi.py 程式時, 其實 Python 程式是仰賴 Flask 網際框架結構來進行資料伺服. \n CMSiMDE 的作動需要 Flask 網際框架, 需要 bs4 與 lxml 進行 content.htm 的頁面解讀, 透過超文件檔案中的 h1, h2 與 h3 由上到下執行循序式分頁, 之後再透過 Javascript 與 css 將 h1, h2, h3 依照樹狀結構, h1 標題為第一階, h2 為第二階, h3 為第三階. \n', 'tags': '', 'url': 'CMSiMDE 程式架構.html'}, {'title': '為何需要網際內容管理', 'text': '全球資訊網無遠弗屆, 而且 WWW 的伺服架構相對於手機 APP 對於使用者而言更加友善, 除了允許多重身分無需實名綁定之外, 可以讓工程師進行各種協同設計, 因此若能廣泛利用網際環境建立各種應用程式環境, 將有助提升設計效益. \n', 'tags': '', 'url': '為何需要網際內容管理.html'}, {'title': '如何建立 CMSiMDE 子模組', 'text': 'git submodule add  https://github.com/mdecourse/cmsimde.git \xa0cmsimde \n 表示要透過 git submodule add 將  https://github.com/mdecourse/cmsimde.git \xa0遠端倉儲當作子模組, 而且將資料存入子目錄 cmsimde 中. \n', 'tags': '', 'url': '如何建立 CMSiMDE 子模組.html'}, {'title': '為何需要以子模組的設計', 'text': '在一個倉儲中帶有子模組的用意是善用分散式設計的做法, 子模組代表一個非由倉儲管理者維護權限所及的單位模組. 意即, 倉儲中程式的執行需要子模組中的資料, 但是倉儲擁有者將子模組視為獨立元件, 並不需要對子模組的內容進行改版. 一旦子模組原始倉儲資料更新, 採用子模組的各倉儲所有者可以決定是否配合跟進, 若不跟進仍有使用既有版本的子模組繼續運作, 原始子模組與採用不同版本子模組的倉儲都不會彼此受到影響. \n', 'tags': '', 'url': '為何需要以子模組的設計.html'}, {'title': '兩種不同的 git clone', 'text': 'git clone  https://github.com/mdecourse/cmsimde.git \n 表示要將 cmsimde 倉儲的資料 clone 到近端, 針對沒有子模組設置的倉儲可以直接以 git clone 取下倉儲資料 \n git clone --recurse-submodules  https://github.com/mdecourse/cp2020.git \n 表示要將 cp2020 倉儲中包含個子模組與可能子模組中的子模組等資料, 全部 clone 到近端. \n', 'tags': '', 'url': '兩種不同的 git clone.html'}, {'title': '假如 CMSiMDE 不設為子模組', 'text': '其實各用戶若希望自行維護 CMSiMDE 網際內容管理系統, 可以直接取下 CMSiMDE 程式資料, 然後將倉儲資料放在 cmsimde 子目錄中, 並將 up_dir 中的資料複製一份到倉儲根目錄, 如此就可以依 CMSiMDE 的用法使用動態與靜態網頁. \n', 'tags': '', 'url': '假如 CMSiMDE 不設為子模組.html'}, {'title': '為何需要有動態網頁與靜態網頁', 'text': '所謂的動態網頁指的是有登入系統配置的網際內容管理系統, 當使用者登入後進行內容管理, 網站會馬上呈現新版本內容, 通常無需進行網頁轉換. \n 所謂的靜態網頁則指網站通常沒有登入系統的配置, 而且通常只包含 html 與 Javascript 資料, 由於沒有登入系統, 因此沒有內容被駭的問題, 除非負責伺服超文件網頁的系統遭駭. \n 而 CMSiMDE 的動態網頁用於編輯網站內容, 而靜態網頁則可以利用 Github Pages, Gitlab Pages 與 Heroku 進行伺服. \n', 'tags': '', 'url': '為何需要有動態網頁與靜態網頁.html'}, {'title': 'CMSiMDE 有甚麼使用上的限制嗎比方說能夠使用那些特殊符號, 為什麼不能使用分號, 以及所謂的標題有沒有最多幾個字元的限制, 另外就是假如標題過長, 會發生甚麼狀況與後果', 'text': '假如在上列頁面標題中加上兩個 "?", 上面這個標題就無法順利分頁, 但是利用 SciTE 編輯 config/content.htm 之後將兩個 "?" 刪除後則可以正確完成分頁. \n 上面的標題字元數超過 80 個, 雖可正常分頁但是在資料展示上就顯得不很方便. \n CMSiMDE 標題不能使用 ":" 的原因在於 Windows 操作系統不允許檔案名稱中有 ":", 因此當 CMSiMDE 動態轉靜態時必須以頁面標題作為該頁的檔案名稱, 而無法完成靜態頁面存檔的問題會讓 CMSiMDE 無法順利將動態資料轉為靜態資料. \n', 'tags': '', 'url': 'CMSiMDE 有甚麼使用上的限制嗎比方說能夠使用那些特殊符號, 為什麼不能使用分號, 以及所謂的標題有沒有最多幾個字元的限制, 另外就是假如標題過長, 會發生甚麼狀況與後果.html'}, {'title': 'HW1', 'text': 'http://mde.tw/cp2020/content/HW1.html \n', 'tags': '', 'url': 'HW1.html'}, {'title': 'PC Hardware', 'text': 'https://oli.cmu.edu/jcourse/lms/students/syllabus.do?section=d87f1d540a0001dc1f2919b17868b65f \n', 'tags': '', 'url': 'PC Hardware.html'}, {'title': 'pch8冷卻 (p.73〜p.75)', 'text': '電腦冷卻 \n 1.主動風冷： 主動空氣冷卻組件由風扇和 鋁 或 銅 製成的冷卻板（散熱器）組成。 風扇將新鮮空氣吹到放置在需要冷卻的組件上方的散熱器上。 散熱器的散熱片 增加 了 金屬板的表面 ， 並 增加 了組件的 熱交換能力 。 \n 優： \n (1)風扇在這些散熱片之間吹動空氣，從而使 熱交換 很 快 。 \n (2)可以 快速去除 散熱片之間產生的 熱空氣 。 \n 缺：產生 微熱的零件永遠 無法冷卻到室溫以下 。 \n 2. 被動風冷：被動空氣冷卻使用散熱器來產生接合的組件冷卻表面。 不過，區別在於散熱器的大小，因為被動空氣冷卻僅 依賴散熱片的大小 來 減少熱量 。 \n 優：被動式空氣冷卻是 最有效 的冷卻方式，因為它 不使用任何電源 進行操作。 \n 缺： 散熱片 必須足夠 大 ，而且它們之間還必須具有 足夠的空間 ，才能可以實現自然的空氣流動。 \n \xa0 \xa0 \xa0\xa0 散熱器 會很 重 。 \n 3. 液體冷卻：液體冷卻利用了熱力學的基本原理，即轉變從較熱的物體轉移到較冷的 物體 。通過 較冷 的物體 變熱 ， 較熱 的物體 變冷 。 \n 優： \n (1)被水冷卻的組件比起空氣 傳遞更多的熱量 。 \n (2)不受環境溫度的影響。 \n (3) 噪音 水平相對 低 。 \n 缺： \n (1)液體冷卻 複雜 \n (2)成本 高 。 \n 內部組件： \n 散熱器 ：散熱器通過使用冷卻風扇有效地冷卻液體，將吸收的轉換轉移到周圍環境中。散熱器上方，散熱器越有效，從而導致其液體溫度和替代組件溫度。 \n 水塊 ：水塊（或散熱器）從吸收吸收轉化。 它包含微翅片，這些微翅片用於增加尺寸並實現更佳的熱傳遞。 當液體流過水塊時，其吸收波長。 如果您使用更有效的阻水劑，則組件的整體溫度將會降低。 \n 水泵 ：水泵提供冷卻迴路中從熱側到冷側的液體循環。 這允許在整個迴路中進行有效的熱傳遞。 沒有良好的水泵，液體將滯留在迴路中，並且不會發生熱傳遞。 \n 儲 ：儲存器單元允許初始液體冷卻安裝後容易除去空氣 ，並作為在溫度波動的冷卻的膨脹區域 。 \n \n 液體冷卻安裝: \n 1.關閉計算機電源並拔下電源插頭 \n 2.打開機箱 \n 3.安裝處理器 \n 4.清潔CPU和水塊，清除灰塵和碎屑 \n 5.使用導熱膏 \n 6.水冷塊代替傳統的散熱器 \n \xa0 \xa0散熱器代替後箱風扇\xa0 \n 7.散熱器連接到水箱 \n 8.重新連接電源 \n 9.打開計算機電源，並確保液體冷卻系統正常運行 \n 10.關閉外殼 \n CPU安裝步驟: \n 1.將CPU安裝到主板的處理器插槽中。 \n 2.清潔CPU頂部和散熱器表面。 \n 3.在CPU和散熱器的表面塗上導熱膏。 \n 4.將散熱器安裝到處理器上。 \n 5.將冷卻風扇連接到散熱器的頂部。 \n 6.確保風扇已通電。 \n 7.每六個月清潔一次風扇葉片和散熱器的灰塵。 \n 機箱風扇 \n 機箱風扇對於消除計算機組件（尤其是視頻卡和CPU）產生的所有熱空氣是不可避免的。 必須排出熱空氣，用冷空氣代替。 通常會發現 較冷的空氣靠近地面 ，因為熱量會上升，因此大多數情況下都設計成冷空氣被前殼風扇從 底部 吸入系統 ，空氣從CPU附近的 機箱後部 以及 圖形處理單元附近的機箱側面 排出。 \n 例: \n 此為常見配置 \n 機箱底部前部靠近驅動器托架（進氣口）的1個風扇。 \n 機箱後部頂部，CPU上方（排氣口之後）和上方的1個風扇。 \n 機箱側面有1個風扇，與GPU相對（進氣）。 \n 此設置將空氣從前部吸入，通過驅動器托架將其引導到視頻卡周圍，然後從排氣風扇中排出。 側風扇將空氣直接壓到最熱的組件（GPU）上，然後由前風扇向上推動，並從後部排氣風扇中導出。 \n \xa0 \xa0\xa0 \n 安裝步驟: \n 1. 確保已關閉PC的電源。 \n 2. 使用十字螺絲刀安裝機箱風扇。 \n 3. 將風扇連接到未使用的風扇接頭連接器上，為風扇供電。 \n 4.整理電纜線。 \n', 'tags': '', 'url': 'pch8冷卻 (p.73〜p.75).html'}, {'title': 'pch8Cooling (p.73〜p.75)', 'text': 'Active Air Cooling \n \n \n Active air cooling components consist of a fan and a cooling plate (heat sink) made of aluminum or copper. A fan blows fresh air on a heat sink placed over the components that need to be cooled. The heat sink’s fins increase the surface of the metal plate and increase the heat exchange capabilities of the component. The fan blows the air between those fins, making the heat exchange quicker and more efficient, as it rapidly removes the heated air that is produced between the fins. There is only one drawback to active air cooling: the component that generates heat can never be cooled below the ambient room temperature. This is because active cooling uses forced air from the room, and the room air cannot cool a component to a lower temperature than the ambient temperature. These components are very reliable, and the cost of this system is quite affordable. \n Passive Air Cooling \n \n \n \n \n Similar to the active air cooling method, passive air cooling uses a heat sink to create a larger cooling surface of a component. The difference lies in the size of the heat sink, though, since passive air cooling relies solely on the size of the fins to reduce the heat. These fins must be large enough and must also have enough space between them so that a natural flow of air can be achieved that will adequately remove the heat. These heat sinks can become quite heavy and require special parts to be fixed over the part to be cooled. Passive air cooling is the most efficient way of cooling in terms of power saving, since it uses no power to operate. The drawback to this method is weight, since heavy and large heat sinks must be fixed over small parts, increasing the total weight of a computer and reducing the usable area inside the case. Additionally, this method doesn’t work well when the ambient temperature is high, because high ambient temperature causes the passive air cooling to become ineffective. \n Liquid Cooling \n Modern CPUs generate twice as much heat as CPUs did five years ago. This is even truer for the GPUs. For example, a powerful dual-processor graphics card can generate as much as 380 watts of heat. Many contemporary machines use multiple processors and graphics cards, making the efficient cooling of these components a priority. Removing such vast amounts of heat in a space-constrained environment such as a computer chassis is traditionally done at the cost of an uncomfortably high noise level from the fan. Liquid cooling minimizes the noise level required. Liquid cooling is also the best solution for rapid heat removal due to the high thermal output of the GPUs and CPUs in gaming systems and high performance computers respectively. A water block normally offers a lower profile cooling solution and it allows double computational power in the same cubic footprint. The liquid cooling system dramatically lowers the operational temperatures and increases the ability to overclock CPUs to higher levels without damage. \n Liquid cooling takes advantage of a basic principle of thermodynamics — that heat moves from warmer objects to cooler objects. As the cooler object gets warmer, the warmer object gets cooler. The sole purpose is to transfer heat (energy) away from critical computer components quickly and effectively. The heat is usually transferred to the surrounding environment by dissipating the heat through the heat sink and radiators. Water has a high level of thermal conductivity, meaning it absorbs heat better than air. Liquid cooling works by running water through the channels in the water block attached to each of the components that require cooling, transferring heat from each part to a radiator that dissipates the heat and keeps the water cool — similar to a car\'s radiator. This lets the processor, graphics card, and other hardware cool down much more effectively. \n Liquid cooling allows the transfer of more heat from the components being cooled than air, making liquid cooling perfect for overclocking and high-performance computer applications. In comparison to air cooling, liquid cooling is not influenced by the ambient temperature, making it a better choice in environments with a high ambient heat. Also, liquid cooling has a relatively low noise level because it uses much quieter and smaller fans than those used in active cooling. \n The major drawbacks of liquid cooling are complexity and cost. Also, liquid cooling can be messy and cause damage when a failure in pipe connections occurs. Liquid cooling also needs a good deal of power to operate the pump. Despite some of these drawbacks, liquid cooling is still popular with gamers because of its efficiency and effectiveness. \n In a liquid cooled system, each component that requires cooling has a cooling plate (heat sink) attached to it. This heat sink, usually made of copper or aluminum, is a hollow plate with an input and an output hose through which the coolant will flow. The circulating pump will circulate the coolant from the radiator to the cooling plates, then to the tank and back to the radiator, where the heat is dissipated. \n Here are more details about each component: \n Radiator : The radiator moves the absorbed heat into the surrounding environment by using a cooling fan to effectively cool the liquid. The bigger the radiator, the more effective it becomes, which results in lower liquid temperature and a lower component temperature. \n Water block : The water block (or heat sink) absorbs the heat from the microprocessor. It contains microfins that are used to boost the surface area for more optimal heat transfer. As the liquid flows through the water block, it absorbs the heat. If you have a more efficient water block, your overall component temperature will decrease. \n Water pump : The water pump provides the circulation of the liquid in the cooling loop from the hot side to the cold side. This allows for effective heat transfer throughout the entire loop. Without a good water pump, the liquid would stagnate in the loop and heat transfer would not occur. \n Reservoir : The reservoir unit allows for easier removal of air after the initial liquid cooling installation and serves as an expansion area for the coolant during temperature fluctuations. \n \n Liquid cooling system. Photo used under CC-BY-NC-ND license from \xa0 Terror Noize . \n \n \n \n \n \n \n For maintenance, it is important to clear the fan blades and heat sink of dust at least every six months. This is a quick and easy maintenance task. Blowing compressed air into the fan blades and across the heat sink fins will keep the cooling system running smoothly. \n Case Fans \n \n \n \n \n Case fans are necessary to remove all the hot air generated by computer components, especially video cards and CPUs. The hot air has to be vented out and replaced by cooler air. Cool air can usually be found closer to the ground, since heat tends to rise, so most cases are designed so that cooler air is pulled into the system at the bottom by the front case fan. Air is then exhausted out the rear-top of the case near the CPU as well as out of the side of the case near the graphics processing unit. \n \n \n \n EXAMPLE: \n \n Here is a common case fan setup: \n 1x fan in the bottom-front of the case, near the drive bays (intake). \n 1x fan in the rear-top of the case, "behind" and above the CPU (exhaust). \n 1x fan in the side of the case, across from the GPU (intake). \n This setup pulls air in through the front, channels it through the drive bays, around the video card, and out the exhaust fan. The side fan forces air directly onto the hottest component (the GPU), and is then pushed up by the front fan and channeled out of the rear exhaust fan. \n \n Case fan. Photo used under CC-BY-SA license from \xa0 William Hook . \n Case Fans: Installation: \n The following steps will enable you to install a case fan. First, you must ensure that your PC is powered off before you install any component in your system. After opening the case, you will need a Phillips head screwdriver in order to remove/install case fans. If you’re replacing a fan, simply remove the old one by unscrewing it from the case and unplugging the cable from the header (or the MOLEX connection, if you have an older system). To mount the new fan, hold the fan up to the mounting position so that the holes for screws line up with the holes in the case. While holding the fan in place with one hand, with your other hand use four screws to secure it in place. Some models use plastic friction clips to hold the fan in place instead of screws. If the system is like this, simply un-snap the clips, remove the fan, and pop the new one in its place. \n After you secure the fan, you need to attach the fan to an unused fan header to provide the fan with power. The headers are keyed to ensure a proper connection and prevent you from plugging them in backwards. Four-pin headers will work with three-pin fans, but you will not be able to control fan speeds, since this is only performed by the fourth pin in the connector. \n When you are done installing the fan, make sure you route your fan and other cables using proper cable management techniques and some zip-ties. Proper cable management prevents the fans from hitting the cables when they spin and also aids in proper airflow to increase cooling efficiency. Be sure to power up the computer and make sure the fan is working properly. \n \n Red case fan. Photo used under CC-BY license from\xa0 Airplane Lane . \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n', 'tags': '', 'url': 'pch8Cooling (p.73〜p.75).html'}, {'title': 'pch9網路概述（p.76〜p.79）', 'text': '地理位置定義的網路 \n 網絡由其所覆蓋的地理位置定義。一個人周圍的區域開始，將區域稱為 個人區域網絡（PAN） 。接下來，我們將擴展擴展到相連 局域網（LAN） ，該替換可以包含整個辦公場所或建築物。再次擴展移動，我們有了 城域網(MAN) ，該城域網通過將多個 LAN 連接在一起而覆蓋了整個城市。最後，我們有 廣域網（WAN） 。這是我們按定位定義的最大網絡，它可以遍及全國，甚至遍及全球。廣域網就是一個很好的例子，因為互聯網將許多網絡連接在一起並遍及全球。 \n 地理網路示意圖： \n \n 個人區域網 （PAN ） \n PAN的範圍很小，大約將 雙手伸向兩側並轉一圈 ，這是大多數 PAN 的物理範圍。藍牙是我們用於創建 PAN 的主要內容之一，儘管 USB 和紅外線也可以用於這些網絡。藍牙的範圍在 1米至100米 之間，具體而言是使用的藍牙類別，但是大多數常見的藍牙設備是替換於10米的第二類設備。 PAN 的一些很好的例子是 USB 硬盤驅動器和筆記本電腦之間的連接，或者是無線連接到汽車立體聲系統的藍牙手機。 \n 局域網（ LAN ） \n 由幾個設備組成，這些設備使計算機可以在 一個較小的地理區域 內部相互連接。最基本的是使用集線器，交換機或無線訪問點將多個工作站連接在一起。且 具有距離限制 ，每個網段通常 限制在100米 。通常， LAN 用於將辦公室的地板或較小網絡中的整個辦公樓聯網。 LAN 通常以 有線 或 無線 方式連接。如果為有線，則使用符合 乙太網路 （ IEEE 802.3 ）標準的非屏蔽雙絞線電纜進行連接；如果為無線，則其使用 Wi-Fi 無線電信號（ IEEE 802.11 ）標准進行連接。 \n 簡易局域網： \n \n 複雜局域網： \n \n 城域網（ MAN ） \n 城域網連接整個城市或縣的分散位置。這比局域網（ LAN ）覆蓋更大的地理區域，但是比廣域網（ WAN ）覆蓋的區域小部分。 \n 城域網示意圖： \n \n 廣域網（ WAN ） \n WAN：將地理位置相距較遠的網絡組件連接在一起。例如：將洛杉磯的辦公室連接到紐約的另一公司辦公室。這可以通過 Internet 的虛擬專用網絡（ VPN ）或使用將城市對實際連接在一起的專用租用線路來完成。或者採用交替連接方法，來自洛杉磯和紐約的兩個直接相連，它們便成為其中的廣域網拓撲的一部分。 \n 廣域網，城域網和局域網 關係： \n \n 通過關係定義的網路 \n 以通過這些分配資源的方式來定義網絡。 \n 1.使用的 客戶/服務器 模型。在客戶端 / 服務器模型中，一個或多個專用服務器向客戶端工作站提供對文件，掃描儀，打印機和其他資源的訪問。由於所有資源都放在幾個關鍵服務器上上，因此可以根據作業功能，網絡特權或部門分配資源，這 簡化 了管理和備份負擔，使網絡可以 集中管理 ，並且可以提供更好的安全性。 \n 2.在 網絡上共享資源 ，稱為對等模型。在對等模型中，所有工作站都被認為是替代的：每台計算機或工作站都直接與其他工作站共享其資源。沒有中央管理。例如，如果我與同事共享打印機，那麼每次同事打印文檔時，該文檔都會通過工作站發送到打印機。這些的缺點是，如果 關閉計算機 ，我的同事將 無法訪問我的資源 ，例如打印機。對等模型下管理的備份狀語從句：要 困難 得多，因為資源位於網絡上的眾多工作站上，使管理任務變得很繁重。此外，當允許節點或工作站之間的訪問時， 沒有真正的方法來保護網絡資源 。點對點資源共享的好處是入門 成本低 。 \n 拓撲定義的網絡 \n 當我們根據網絡的拓撲定義網絡時，我們會同時考慮 物理和邏輯 拓撲，並且這兩種拓撲都 不必針對單個網絡進行匹配 。物理拓撲決定了設備的物理連接方式，而邏輯拓撲決定了流量如何以邏輯方式流經網絡。拓撲類型很多，包括 總線 . 環形 . 星形 . 全網格 和 混合拓撲 。當前，使用最廣泛的模型是使用乙太網路的 物理星形 和 邏輯總線 拓撲。 \n 總線拓撲 : \n 總線拓撲通常使用 一根電纜穿過需要網絡連接的區域 ，每個希望連接到網絡的設備都通過該電纜連接。設備使用 T型連接器 或 穿孔抽頭 插入電纜。穿孔抽頭實際上是一種連接，其中金屬齒咬入電纜，與電纜內部的銅線進行物理連接。儘管總線拓撲是一種較舊的技術，基本上已不再使用，但在某些情況下仍可以將其作為邏輯實現。 \n \n 環形拓撲 : \n 通常使用在 環形迴路中運行的電纜 ，每個設備都連接到環形。數據在環上沿單個方向傳播。環形拓撲最常見的用途是與 骨幹光纖網絡 一起使用。 光纖分佈式數據接口（FDDI） 是用於在 LAN 中的光纖線上傳輸數據的一組標準。 FDDI 通常使用 兩個反向旋轉 的環來 提供更多的冗餘 。每個設備都通過在令牌環周圍傳遞令牌來等待其在令牌環上進行通信。因此， 環形拓撲網絡 也稱為 令牌環網絡 。由於有兩個反向旋轉的環，因此 FDDI 傾向於提供 比標準總線拓撲更多的冗餘 。但是，在大多數 LAN 中， 總線 和 環形拓撲 都很快被 星形拓撲 取代。 \n \n 星形拓撲 : \n 為迄今為止使用的最常見的拓撲。我們發現幾乎所有 局域網 都使用 星型拓撲 。星型拓撲的所有設備都連接到一個點。單個連接點可以是集線器或交換機。在大多數現代網絡中，單個連接點將是一個交換機。 星形拓撲 是當今 主要的物理拓撲 ，儘管它們並不用作邏輯拓撲 . 乙太網電纜，也稱為非屏蔽雙絞線，在採用星形配置的局域網中非常普遍。但是， 光纖連接 也可以用於 高速 或 高安全性 網絡。星形拓撲的缺點是 會造成單點故障 。如果中央設備（如交換機）發生故障， 整個網絡會失敗 。與總線和環形網絡品種不同，星形拓撲結構具有 減少費用 並 易於擴展 的優勢。 \n \n 全網狀拓撲 : \n 到目前為止，此拓撲是 最冗餘 . 最昂貴 的拓撲，因為網絡中的每個節點或工作站都 直接 連接到每個其他節點。儘管這提供了最佳的路由，但 維護和操作非常昂貴 。可以使用公式 x = n（n-1）/ 2 計算任意數量的節點所需的連接數。例如，如果您有六個節點，則需要 15 條電纜才能將它們彼此連接。如果您有 50 個節點，則需要 1225 個單獨的連接。所以可以知到為什麼幾乎不將該拓撲用於局域網，因為計 算機數量過多 會導致 連接數量增加過快 。 \n \n 部分網格拓撲 : \n 為了解決由 全網格拓撲 創建的 成本 問題，工程師創建了部分網格拓撲。部分網狀拓撲實際上是 混合全網狀拓撲 。它 提供 某些站點之間的 冗餘 和 最佳路由 ，同時 避免 了連接每個站點的 開銷 。但是，為了成功創建它，必須 考慮網絡流量模式 以有效地進行設計。 \n 例 :   如果我們有兩個非常繁忙的站點，例如加利福尼亞州的洛杉磯和紐約州的紐約，我們可能希望通過將它們連接到第三個城市（例如華盛頓特區）為他們 提供更多的冗餘 。但是，速度較慢的站點（例如，南卡羅來納州格林維爾）可能只需要連接到這三個站點之一，然後就可以將其 用作連接 其他兩個站點的 起點 。這與我們的航空旅行系統非常相似，在航空旅行系統中，我們將大城市直接連接在一起，避免了直接飛往小城市的航班。例如 : 如果有人想從格林維爾飛往洛杉磯，他們會先從格林維爾飛往華盛頓特區，然後再乘較大的飛機直接從華盛頓飛往洛杉磯。 \n 相同的概念適用於部分網格拓撲。部分網狀網絡在最大和最繁忙的站點之間 添加了額外的資源 （連接），同時仍為大型站點之一提供較小的站點，但 服務卻最少 。較小的站點將大型集線器用作連接到網絡其餘部分的起點。 \n 網絡拓撲分類圖 : \n \n', 'tags': '', 'url': 'pch9網路概述（p.76〜p.79）.html'}, {'title': 'pch9Networking Overview（p.76〜p.79）', 'text': 'Overview \n \n \n In this module, we are going to cover the various types of networks, including local area networks, wide area networks, personal area networks, and metropolitan area networks. Next, we will cover the various network relationships, such as client/server and peer-to-peer, and focus on the types of resources our networks use. Finally, we will talk about the topologies of our networks, such as the bus, the ring, the star, the full mesh, and hybrid network topologies. \n Network Defined By Geography \n \n \n \n \n Networks are defined by the geography they cover. We start with the area around a single person, with this area being termed the personal area network (PAN). Next, we expand outward to the local area network (LAN), which can contain an entire office floor or building. Moving outward again, we have the metropolitan area network, which covers the area across the city by connecting multiple LANs together. Finally, we have the wide area network (WAN). This is the largest network we define by geography and it can go across the country or even across the world. A great example of a WAN is the Internet, since it connects many networks together and stretches across the globe. \n \n Geographic networks. Image used under CC-BY license from \xa0 Jason Dion . \n Personal Area Network \n A PAN has a very small range limited to just a few meters. If you stretch your hands out at your sides and spin around in a circle, this is the physical range of most PANs. Bluetooth is one of the main things we use to create a PAN, although USB and infrared can also be used for these networks. Bluetooth has a range between one meter and 100 meters depending on which class of Bluetooth you are using, but most common Bluetooth devices are class two devices limited to 10 meters. Some good examples of PANs are the connection between a USB hard drive and a laptop, or a Bluetooth cellphone connecting to your car stereo system wirelessly. \n Local Area Network \n The next type of network defined by geography is the LAN, which stands for local area network. The local area network is comprised of several devices that allow computers to connect to each other within a small geographic area. A LAN is, at its most basic, a connection of several workstations together using a hub, switch, or wireless access point. LANs have a limited distance associated with them, with each network segment usually limited to 100 meters or less. Generally, a LAN is used to network the floor of an office, or possibly the entire office building in smaller networks. LANs are generally connected in either a wired or wireless manner. If wired, they are connected using unshielded twisted pair cable using the Ethernet (IEEE 802.3) standard; if wireless, they are connected using Wi-Fi radio signal (IEEE 802.11) standards. \n \n Simple LAN diagram. Public domain image obtained from \xa0 Wierzbadark . \n \n \n Caption. Complex LAN diagram. Used with permission. Copyright: \xa0 ohmega 1982/123 RF Stock Photo . \n Metropolitan Area Networks \n Another way we can geographically define our networks is as a MAN. A metropolitan area network connects scattered locations across the city or county. This covers a larger geographical area than a local area network, but also a much smaller area than a wide-area network. \n \n MAN diagram. Image used under CC-BY-SA license from \xa0 Greta Bynum . \n Wide Area Networks \n The WAN is used to connect network components that are geographically separated over vast distances together. An example of a WAN would be to connect an office in Los Angeles to another corporate office in New York. This can be done using virtual private networks (VPNs) over the Internet or using dedicated leased lines that would physically connect the city pairs together. Regardless of the method of connection, once the two local area networks from Los Angeles and New York are connected, they become part of the larger wide area network topology. \n \n Wide area network, metropolitan area network, and local area network. Image used under CC-BY-SA license from \xa0 Suwimon bunmak . \n \n \n \n Network Defined by Relationships \n In addition to defining networks by geography or how much area they cover, you can also define them by the way they allocate their resources. The first method is what we call a client/server model. In a client/server model, a dedicated server or servers provide(s) access to files, scanners, printers, and other resources to client workstations. This simplifies the administration and backup burden, making the network centrally administered, and can provide better security because resources can be allocated according to job function, network privilege, or department, since all of the resources are located on a few key servers. The second way of sharing resources on the network is called the peer-to-peer model. In the peer-to-peer model, all workstations are considered equals: each computer or workstation shares its resources directly with the other workstations. There is no central administration. For example, if I shared my printer with my coworkers, then each time my coworker printed a document, it would be sent to the printer through my workstation. The drawback to this is that if my computer is turned off, my coworkers lose access to my resources, such as my printer. The administration and backup under the peer-to-peer model is much more difficult, since resources are located on numerous workstations across the network, making administrative tasks burdensome. Furthermore, there is no real way of securing network resources when allowing access between nodes or workstations. The benefit of peer-to-peer resource sharing is the low cost of entry, since no dedicated servers or specialized operating systems are required to share the resources. \n Network Defined by Topology \n \n Besides geography and relationships, we can also define our networks by their topology. When we define our networks by their topology, we consider both the physical and logical topology, and both of these topologies do not have to match for a single network. The physical topology determines how the devices are physically connected, while the logical topology determines how the traffic flows across the network in a logical manner. There are many types of topologies, including bus, ring, star, full mesh, and hybrid. Currently, the most widely used model is a physical star and a logical bus topology using Ethernet. \n Bus Topology \n \n \n Bus topology typically uses a single cable running through the area that needs network connectivity, with each device that wishes to connect to the network tapping into that cable. The devices tap into the cable using either a T connector (see diagram below) or a vampire tap. A vampire tap is actually a type of connection where a metal tooth bites into the cable, making a physical connection with the copper wire running inside the cable. While bus topology is an older technology and not commonly used anymore, physically, it can still be found as a logical implementation in some instances. \n \n Bus topology diagram. Image used under CC-BY-SA license from \xa0 Nattydusadee . \n Ring Topology \n \n \n \n \n \n Ring topology typically uses a cable running in a circular loop, with each device connected to the ring. Data travels in a single direction around the ring. The most common use of ring topology is with backbone fiber networks. Fiber distributed data interface (FDDI) is a set of standards for transmitting data on fiber-optic lines in a LAN. FDDI commonly uses two counter-rotating rings to provide more redundancy. Each device waits its turn to communicate on the ring by passing a token around the ring. Therefore, ring topology networks are also called token ring networks. As there are two counter-rotating rings, FDDI tends to provide a little more redundancy than a standard bus topology. However, both bus and ring topologies were quickly replaced in most LANs by the star topology. \n \n Ring topology diagram. Photo used under CC-BY-SA license from \xa0 Marisa . pr . \n Star Topology \n \n \n \n \n \n Star topology is by far the most common topology in use today. We find star topologies in use in nearly all local area networks. All the devices of the star topology connect to a single point. That single point of connection can be a hub or switch. In most modern networks, the single connection point will be a switch. Star topologies are the dominant physical topology today, although they are not always used as the logical topology. Ethernet cabling, also known as unshielded twisted-pair, is very commonly employed in local area networks using a star configuration. However, fiber-optic connections can also be used for high-speed or high-security networks. The downside with the star topology is that it creates a single point of failure. If a central device such as a switch fails, the entire network fails as well. Star topologies have the benefit of reduced expense and make expansion very easy, unlike bus and ring network varieties. \n \n Star topology diagram. Photo used under CC-BY-SA license from \xa0 Marisa. pr . \n Full Mesh Topology \n \n \n \n \n \n To deal with the issue of redundancy, the full mesh topology was created. This topology is by far the most redundant, and expensive, topology because every node or workstation in the network is directly connected to every other node. While this provides optimal routing, it is very expensive to maintain and operate. The number of connections required for any number of nodes can be calculated by using the formula, x = n(n-1)/2. For example, if you have six nodes, that would require 15 cables to connect them all to each other. If you had 50 nodes, that would require 1225 separate connections. You can certainly see why this topology is almost never used for local area networks, as the number of machines would drive the number of connections up too quickly. \n \n Photo used under CC-BY-SA license from \xa0 Marisa. pr . \n Partial Mesh Topology \n \n \n \n \n \n To solve the cost issues created by the full mesh topology, engineers created the partial mesh topology. Partial mesh topology is really a hybrid full mesh topology. It provides redundancy and optimal routing between some sites, while avoiding the expense of connecting every single site. In order to create this successfully, though, you must consider the network traffic patterns to design it efficiently. \n \n EXAMPLE: \n \n \n If we have two sites which are very busy, such as Los Angeles, CA and New York, NY, we may want to provide them with additional redundancy by connecting them to a third city, such as Washington, DC. But a slower site, maybe somewhere like Greenville, SC, might only need to be connected to one of those three sites and can then use that as a jumping off point to connect to the other two sites. This works very similar to our air travel system, where we connect the large cities together directly, and we avoid direct flights to small cities. For example, if someone wanted to fly from Greenville to Los Angeles they would first take a flight from Greenville to Washington DC, then a direct flight on a larger plane to Los Angeles from Washington. \n \n \n \n The same concept applies in a partial mesh topology. Partial mesh adds additional resources (connections) between the biggest and busiest sites, while still providing the smaller sites with minimal service to one of the large hub sites. The smaller site uses the large hub as a jumping off point to the rest of the network. \n \n Mesh network topology diagram. Public domain image obtained from \xa0 Wikimedia Commons . \n \n \n Diagram of multiple classifications of network topologies. Public domain image obtained from \xa0 Maksim . \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n', 'tags': '', 'url': 'pch9Networking Overview（p.76〜p.79）.html'}, {'title': 'pch10網路設備 (p.80~p.82)', 'text': '網絡設備根據其用途而有所不同，例如 集線器 . 交換機 . 路由器 . 網橋 . 網絡適配器 和 媒體 。在討論設備時，您應注意其用途，優點和局限性。我們將探討如何安裝網絡適配器。 \n 集線器 \n 為 最簡單 的網絡設備之一，用於 多個網絡設備 和 工作站 相互 連接 ，從而形成一個網絡。集線器也稱為 多端口中繼器 。集線器通過在一個端口中接收信號並將該信號重新廣播到其所有其他端口來工作。標準集線器 沒有任何“智能” （能夠根據不同情況或要求進行更改的能力），因此我們通常將它們稱為 “ 啞集線器 ” 。集線器可以分為 主動 或 被動 兩種。活動集線器會在其所有端口上重複接收到的信號，並將該信號放大到最大強度。無源集線器僅重複信號而不增加任何放大。集線器是一種較舊的技術，可 輕鬆增加可用端口的數量 ，但這會導致 過多的網絡錯誤和衝突 。集線器有較新的設備，稱為智能集線器。 智能集線器 為實質具有增強功能（例如，使用簡單網絡管理協議（ SNMP ））的活動集線器。 \n 乙太網路集線器的三種基本類型如下： \n 1. 無源集線器–重複信號而不放大 \n 2. 有源集線器–重複放大信號 \n 3. 智能集線器–具有增強功能的活動集線器（例如：SNMP） \n 集線器內部 沒有設計完好的安全性 ，因為它們只是將從一個端口接收的所有信息重新廣播到另一個端口。本質上，集線器 僅依賴於連接的工作站來“偵聽”其端口上的信息 （如果該信息專門針對該工作站）。當信息沒有發送給它時，工作站應該只是忽略數據。但是，可以將網卡置於 “ 混雜 ” 模式，在該模式下，網卡將 偵聽所有流量 ，而不管該流量指向哪個工作站。這使集線器非常 不安全 。 \n 集線器的另一個缺點是 必須共享帶寬 ，因為所有設備都在同一個衝突域中運行。因此，如果您有一個 100 Mbps 的集線器，但將四個設備連接到該集線器，則每個設備將有效地以 25 Mbps 的速度運行。使用 16 端口， 24 端口或 48 端口集線器時，這可能會導致 網絡流量大幅下降 。 \n LAN網絡圖 : \n \n 網橋 \n 因為集線器與所有在單個衝突域中起作用的設備一起運行，所以需要一個可以 將該衝突域分解為較小單元 的網絡設備，以幫助網絡更高效地運行。例如，如果一個集線器連接到另一個集線器，則它們都在單個衝突域下運行 \xa0 。橋用於將兩個集線器連接在一起，但仍使集線器的衝突域保持分離。多個網段的這種互連在一起使網絡可以 擴展為大型網絡 ，而 不會降低該網絡的性能 。網橋比集線器更具智能；實際上，他們實際上是在分析源 媒體存取控制（MAC） 地址在進入網橋的幀數中，並根據這些地址填充內部 MAC 表。未來的路由決策將基於那些目標 MAC 地址。通過僅將信息轉發到與網絡設備關聯的根集線器，這種基於幀中目標 MAC 地址的智能轉發可 減少網絡流量 。 \n 交換機 \n 用於將 多個網段連接在一起 ，無論它們是從交換機到交換機還是從工作站到工作站。交換機上的每個端口都充當其自己的衝突域。交換機是集線器和網橋的演進。本質上，交換機上的每個端口都像是集線器一樣工作，帶有將集線器的端口連接到工作站的網橋，從而 將網絡衝突的機會降低到零 。 \n 交換機是 智能設備 ，它們根據其學習到的 MAC 地址並放置在其 MAC 表中來做出轉發決策。交換機在輸入源 MAC 地址時會對其進行分析，然後以幀的形式填充源 IP 地址，以使其與交換機端口匹配。這允許交換機僅將幀轉發到單個交換機端口上的正確設備，從而 提高安全性 和 網絡速度 。 \n 如果交換機接收到幀，但在其轉發表中沒有目標 MAC 地址，則它將將該幀分流到除了源以外的所有端口上，以請求目標 MAC 地址的位置。交換器可以分解衝突域，但需創建 廣播域 。 \n 因為無論信息卡是否處於 “ 混雜 ” 模式，只有信息所針對的設備才能收到副本，所以 安全性提高 了，。這在操作上 類似 於 老式的電話接線員總機 。如果信息未發送到您的端口，則您的端口將不會收到該信息。另外，由於每個端口都在其自己的衝突域中，因此 網絡速度得以提高 。無論網絡上有多少設備，每個交換機端口都 可以全速運行 ，因此對於 100 Mbps 交換機，每個設備都以 100 Mbps 的速度運行。 \n 網絡圖 ( 交換機 ): \n \n 路由器 \n 路由器相對於網路配置圖的 第3層（數據包） ，而交換機位於 第2層（幀） 。路由器根據 IP地址 將網段分開，並且僅在 配置時 將數據包轉發出網段。這種設計可以分解由交換機創建的廣播域。由網絡專業人員決定將路由器配置為將不同的網絡連接在一起並執行智能路由決策。路由器與計算機的關係最為密切，因為它具有處理器和複雜的操作系統。路由器比較數據包源和目標的 IP 地址，並基於此邏輯地址（例如， IPv4 和 IPv6 地址）將流量轉發到網絡或從網絡轉發流量。路由器通常是功能豐富的設備，並且支持多種接口類型，包括 非屏蔽雙絞線 . 光纖 和 同軸電纜 連接。像交換機一樣，路由器上的每個端口 都是一個單獨的衝突域 。使用訪問控制列表，路由器可以根據 端口或地址阻止對網絡的訪問 。這種阻塞增加了 網絡的安全性 。 \n 網絡圖 ( 路由器 ): \n \n 網絡適配器 \n 用於通過使用媒體將工作站連接到網絡。可以通過幾種方式將網絡適配器內置到設備的主板中： \n 1.使用 集成端口集群 。 \n 2.通過使用 內部擴展卡 （ PCIe . PCI 或 mini-PCIe ）添加到工作站。 \n 3.通過使用 外部連接的卡 ，例如 USB 或 PCMCIA 。 \n 網絡適配器有兩種主要類型： 有線 和 無線 。有線卡支持各種電纜類型，例如 非屏蔽雙絞線（UTP） . 光纖 和 同軸電纜 。這些各種電纜類型稱為 媒體 。 \n 媒體 \n 用於對 兩個設備端口之間 （例如計算機和交換機之間）的物理連接進行分類的術語。介質由 銅纜 ， 光纜 或 even radio frequency waves （用於 Wi-Fi 網絡）組成。介質的 成本差異很大 ，從無線電波的免費成本到非屏蔽雙絞線（銅纜）的價格便宜，再到光纖電纜的價格昂貴。媒體的類型確定 特定網絡的帶寬速度 ， 容量 和 距離 限制。 \n 網絡圖 ( 媒體 ): 箭頭指向處 \n \n 安裝網絡適配器 \n 有時可能需要安裝 附加網絡接口卡（NIC） 。當前的台式機主板的後方輸入 / 輸出（ I / O ）面板上應 具有內置的NIC 。 如果內置 NIC 出現 故障 ，或者 需要升級 以匹配當前的局域網（ LAN ）規格（即從 10/100 BaseT 到 10/100 ），則安裝附加卡可以使機器 保持運行狀態 。  / 1000 或 10GBaseT ）。 \n 安裝 NIC 操作步驟： \n \n 檢查文檔以確認哪個 NIC 將與您的擴展插槽（ PCI 或 PCIe ）和 LAN 要求相匹配。確保適配器可與主板配合使用。 \n 關閉計算機電源，然後從計算機上斷開主電源線。 \n 按照安全維修慣例（正確的接地 / 防靜電皮帶），打開計算機的側蓋，檢查可用的擴展槽。 \n 匹配新 NIC 卡的連接器 / 引腳，並驗證它是否與建議的插槽匹配。 \n 從背面板上卸下相應的計算機 PCI 選件插槽蓋。 \n 將 NIC 的連接器對準擴展插槽，並在將支架向上推至計算機的背面板上時將其牢固就位，以確保正確對齊。用通常提供的螺釘擰緊新的 NIC 。 \n 請按照安全維修步驟關閉計算機的側蓋。 \n 重新連接主電源線。 \n 打開機器電源。 \n \n 安裝 NIC 硬件後，驅動程序應根據 操作系統自動安裝 。對於 Windows （ Vista / Win7 / Win8.1 / Win10 ），請 驗證網絡和共享中心中的連接 。對於 Linux ，請轉到網絡設置，然後根據 Linux 發行版（例如 Red Hat Linux 或 Ubuntu ）在線搜索適當的驅動程序 \xa0 。 \n 帶有同軸端口的 NIC: \n \n', 'tags': '', 'url': 'pch10網路設備 (p.80~p.82).html'}, {'title': 'pch10Networking Hardware (p.80~p.82)', 'text': 'Overview \n \n \n Network devices vary according to their purpose. In this module, we will discuss various devices, such as hubs, switches, routers, bridges, network adapters, and media. As we discuss the devices, you should pay attention to their uses, their benefits, and their limitations. We will also explore how to install a network adapter. \n Hub \n \n \n \n \n Hubs are among the most simplistic networking devices and are used to connect multiple network devices and workstations to each other, thereby forming a network. Hubs are also known as multiport repeaters. A hub works by accepting a signal in one port and rebroadcasting that same signal out to all of its other ports. Standard hubs do not have any “intelligence” (ability to change in response to varying situations or requirements), so we often refer to them as “dumb hubs.” Hubs can be classified as either active or passive. An active hub repeats the signal it receives on all of its ports and amplifies that signal to full strength. Passive hubs only repeat the signal without adding any amplification. Hubs are an older technology that can be used to easily increase the number of ports available, but this can lead to excessive network errors and collisions. There are newer variants of hubs called smart hubs. Smart hubs are essentially active hubs with enhanced feature sets, such as the use of simple network management protocol (SNMP). \n Three basic types of Ethernet hubs are as follows: \n \n Passive hub – repeats signal with no amplification \n Active hub – repeats signal with amplification \n Smart hub – active hub with enhanced features (ex: SNMP) \n \n Hubs have no inherent security designed within them because they simply rebroadcast all the information received from one port to every other port. Essentially, hubs rely on the connected workstations to only “listen” to the information on their port if that information is specifically addressed to that workstation. When the information is not addressed to it, the workstation is supposed to simply ignore the data. But a network card can be placed into “promiscuous” mode, where it will listen to all traffic, regardless of which workstation that traffic is addressed to. This makes hubs very insecure. \n Another drawback of hubs is that they have to share bandwidth, as all devices operate in one collision domain. Therefore, if you have a 100 Mbps hub, but connect four devices to that hub, your devices will effectively be operating at 25 Mbps each. This can lead to huge slowdowns in your network traffic when using a 16-, 24-, or 48-port hub. \n \n LAN Network Diagram. Copyright: \xa0 ohmega 1982/123 RF Stock Photo . \n Bridges \n \n \n \n \n \n Because hubs operate with all devices acting in a single collision domain, a network device that could break up that collision domain into smaller units is required to help the network operate more efficiently. For example, if a hub is connected to another hub, they both operate under a single \xa0 collision domain \xa0 . A bridge is used to connect two hubs together, but still keep the hubs’ collision domains separate. This interconnection of multiple network segments together allows networks to scale into large networks without significantly decreasing the performance of that network. Bridges are smarter than hubs; in fact, they actually analyze the source \xa0 media access control (MAC) addresses \xa0 in the frames entering the bridge and populate an internal MAC table based on those addresses. Future routing decisions are based upon those destination MAC addresses. This intelligent forwarding based on the destination MAC address in the frame allows for a decrease in network traffic by only forwarding information to the root hub associated with the network device. Network switches, which we will discuss, are the evolution of hubs and bridges. \n Switches \n \n \n \n \n Switches are used to connect multiple network segments together, whether they connect from switch to switch, or switch to workstation. Each port on a switch acts as its own collision domain. A switch is an evolution from a hub and bridge. Essentially, each port on a switch operates as if it were a hub with a bridge connecting the ports of the hub to the workstation, thereby reducing the chance of a collision on the network to zero. \n Switches are intelligent devices that make forwarding decisions based upon the MAC addresses they learn and place in their MAC tables. A switch analyzes the source MAC addresses in frames as they enter the switch, and then populates the switch’s internal MAC table with the addresses to match them with the switch ports. This allows the switch to forward the frame only to the correct device on a single switch port, thereby increasing security and network speed. \n If a switch receives a frame but does not have the destination MAC address in its forwarding table, it will flood the frame to all ports except the source to solicit the location of the destination MAC address. Switches break up collision domains but create \xa0 broadcast domains \xa0 . \n Security is increased because only the device to which the information is addressed can receive a copy, regardless of whether the card is in “promiscuous” mode. This is similar in operation to an old-fashioned telephone operator switchboard. If the information isn’t addressed to your port, your port won’t receive the information. Also, because each port is in its own collision domain, the network speed is increased. Regardless of how many devices are on the network, each switch port has full-speed operations, so for a 100 Mbps switch, each device operates at 100 Mbps. \n \n Network diagram with switch. Image used under CC-BY license from \xa0 Jason Dion . \n Routers \n \n \n \n \n \n Routers move data packets (layer 3), as opposed to switches (layer 2), which move frames. Routers separate network segments based on IP addressing and will only forward packets out of the segment when configured to do so. This design breaks up broadcast domains created by switches. It is up to the network professional to configure the router to connect different networks together and perform intelligent routing decisions. A router is most closely associated with a computer in that it has a processor and a sophisticated OS. The router compares the IP address of the source and destination of the packet and forwards traffic to/from a network based on this logical address (IPv4 and IPv6 addresses, for example). Routers are typically feature-rich devices and support a wide range of interface types, including unshielded twisted pair, fiber optic, and coaxial cable connections. Like a switch, each port on a router is a separate collision domain. Using access control lists, routers have the ability to block access to networks based on ports or addresses. This blocking adds to the network’s security. \n \n Network diagram with router. Image used under CC-BY license from \xa0 Jason Dion . \n Network Adapter \n The network adapter is used to connect a workstation to the network through the use of media. The network adapter can be built in to the motherboard of the device in several ways: \n \n \n \n \n \n \n Using an integrated port cluster. \n Added to a workstation through the use of an internal expansion card (PCIe, PCI, or mini-PCIe). \n Through the use of an externally connected card, such as USB or PCMCIA. \n \n There are two main types of network adapters: wired and wireless. The wired cards support various cable types, such as unshielded twisted pair (UTP), fiber optic, and coaxial cabling. These various cable types are called media. \n Media \n \n \n \n \n Media is the term used to categorize the physical connection between two device ports, such as between a computer and a switch. Media is made up of copper cable, fiber-optic cable, or even radio frequency waves (as used in Wi-Fi networks). Media varies greatly in cost, from free for radio waves, to cheap for unshielded twisted pair (copper cable), to expensive for fiber-optic cabling. The type of media determines the bandwidth speed, capacity, and distance limitations for a particular network. We will discuss media in more depth in a future module. \n \n Network diagram with arrows pointing to connection media. Image used under CC-BY license from \xa0 Jason Dion . \n Install a Network Adapter \n There are times when you may need to install an add-on network interface card (NIC). Current desktop motherboards should have a built-in NIC on the rear input/output (I/O) panel. Installing an add-on card can keep a machine in service if the built-in NIC is defective or if you need to upgrade to match the current local area network (LAN) specifications (i.e., from a 10/100 BaseT to 10/100/1000 or 10GBaseT). \n To install an NIC, follow these steps: \n \n Check documentation to verify which NIC will match your expansion slots (PCI or PCIe) and the LAN requirements. Ensure that the adapter will work with the motherboard. \n Power down the computer and disconnect the main power cord from the machine. \n Following safe repair practice (proper grounding/anti-static strap), open the side cover of the computer to inspect available expansion slots. \n Match the connector/pinouts of the new NIC card and verify it matches the proposed slot. \n Remove the corresponding computer PCI option slot cover from the back panel. \n Line up the connector of the NIC to the expansion slot and seat it firmly as you guide the bracket up to the back panel of the computer, ensuring proper alignment. Tighten the new NIC with the screw that is usually supplied. \n Close the side cover of the computer following safe repair procedures. \n Reconnect the main power cord. \n Power up the machine. \n \n After the NIC hardware is installed, the drivers should install automatically, depending on the operating system. For Windows (Vista/Win7/Win8.1/Win10), verify connectivity in the network and sharing center. For Linux, go to network settings, and search online for the appropriate driver depending on the \xa0 Linux distribution \xa0 , such as Red Hat Linux or Ubuntu). \n \n NIC with coaxial port. Photo used under CC-BY license from \xa0 Commons . \n \n Intel 82574L gigabit Ethernet NIC PCI express x1 card. Photo used under CC-BY license from \xa0 Commons . \n \n \n \n \n \n', 'tags': '', 'url': 'pch10Networking Hardware (p.80~p.82).html'}, {'title': 'pch11網路媒體 (p.83 p.84)', 'text': '在本章節中，我們將討論各種類型的網絡媒體。我們將從光纖電纜開始，然後討論雙絞線電纜和同軸電纜。對於每種電纜類型，我們將討論連接器的外觀，特性和類型，以及速度和限制。 \n 光纖電纜 \n 其電纜的中心使用 玻璃芯 構成，該芯層被包層圍繞。為了將數據從電纜的一端發送到另一端，可使用來自 發光二極管（LED） 或 激光的光沿電纜中心的玻璃纖維 向下傳輸信號。由於數據是通過 光 傳輸的，因此 不受電磁干擾（EMI）的影響 ，電磁干擾會影響傳統的 銅基電纜 ，如 雙絞線 和 同軸電纜 。光纖具有 無需使用中繼器 就可以 遠距離 （許多英里）發送數據的能力。由於它們的 大帶寬 和以 光速 傳播 信息，它們還可以攜帶大量數據。它們的帶寬可以 每秒千兆比特 或甚至 兆兆比特 來度量。 \n 光纖電纜 : \n \n 依 內部芯線大小 ，有以下兩種不同的光纖電纜 : \n 1.多模光纜（ MMF ） : \n 芯線比單模光纜 大 。多模光纖的纖芯尺寸為 62.5微米 。 MMF 的較大芯線實現了從電纜一端到另一端的 多種 傳播模式。這樣一來，單根光纖就可以在其上 傳輸多個信號 ，而每個信號的反射角度都會稍有不同。當光線到達目的地時，信號然後被轉換回 1s 和 0s ，並通過網絡接口卡傳遞到計算機。多模光纖通常用於較 短距離 的光纖連接中，例如從路由器到交換機，從交換機到交換機或從服務器到交換機。 \n 2.單模光纜（ SMF ） : \n 芯線比多模光纜 小 。單模光纜的芯尺寸為 10微米 。 SMF 的較小芯線僅允許光從電纜一端到另一端的 單一 傳播模式。這種直通連接允許數據在 沒有中繼器的情況下 傳輸的距離比使用 MMF 傳輸的 距離 更 長 。當光線到達目的地時，信號然後被轉換回 1 和 0 ，並通過網絡接口卡傳遞到計算機。單模光纖通常用於 超長距離 的光纖連接中，例如從一個局域網到另一個局域網的骨干連接。 \n 光纖電纜連接器 \n 電纜的兩端有四種不同的連接器形式 : \n 1.用戶連接器（ SC ） : \n 一種光纖電纜連接器，與普通的音頻和視頻電纜類似，它使用 推挽機制 鎖入端口。如果要啟用雙向傳輸以發送和接收數據，則需要使用 兩根光纖電纜 ，因此有時會使用 雙SC連接器 。 \n 2.筆直連接器（ ST ） :   是使用 卡口插頭和插座 的光纖電纜連接器。它是大多數使用光纖電纜進行 商業佈線 的 首選標準連接器 ，並且在光纖網絡中 非常常見 。 \n 3.朗訊連接器（ LC ） : \n 是光纖 SC 連接器的 微型版本 。它看上去有點像 SC ，但 尺寸只有一半 ，只有 1.25 毫米而不是 2.5 毫米的插芯，因此在 小區域 （例如 24 端口交換機的前面板）連接 多個設備 時非常有用。 \n 4.機械傳輸註冊插孔連接器（ MT-RJ ） :   一種光纖電纜連接器，其 尺寸小 ，在 小型設備 中非常受歡迎。該連接器 容納兩根光纖 ，並與 插頭上的定位銷 配對。通常發現這些連接器將開關連接到配線架，因為兩個設備的 前面板 都 有有限的區域 。 \n', 'tags': '', 'url': 'pch11網路媒體 (p.83 p.84).html'}, {'title': 'pch11Networking Media (p.83 p.84)', 'text': 'Overview \n \n \n In this module, we’re going to discuss the various types of network media. We will begin with fiber-optic cable and then discuss twisted pair cable and coaxial cable. For each of these cable types, we will discuss appearance, characteristics, and types of connectors, as well as speed and limitations. \n Fiber-Optic Cable \n \n \n \n \n Fiber-optic cables are constructed by using a glass core at the center of the cable that is surrounded by cladding. In order to send data from one end of the cable to the other, light from a light-emitting diode (LED) or laser is used to transmit the signal down the glass fiber at the center of the cable. Because the data is being transmitted using light, it is immune to the effects of electromagnetic interference (EMI) that impact traditional copper-based cables, such as twisted pair and coaxial cables. Fiber-optic cables possess the ability to send the data a very far distance (many miles) without the use of a repeater. They also can carry a significant amount of data due to their large bandwidth and the information traveling at light speed. Their bandwidth can be measured in gigabits or even terabits per second. There are two types of fiber cables: multimode and single-mode fiber. \n \n Fiber-optic cable. Photo used under CC-BY-NC-ND license from \xa0 Craig Rodway . \n \n Multimode fiber cables (MMF) contain a larger core than the single-mode variety. The core size for a multimode fiber is 62.5 microns. A micron is a very small unit of measurement—it is actually even smaller than the width of a human hair. MMF’s larger core enables multiple modes of travel for the light from one end of the cable to the other. This allows a single fiber to carry multiple signals across it, with each signal being transmitted at a slightly different reflective angle. When the light reaches the destination, the signals are then converted back into 1s and 0s and passed to the computer by the network interface card. Multimode fiber is commonly used in shorter distance fiber connections, such as from a router to a switch, a switch to a switch, or a server to a switch. \n Single-mode fiber cables (SMF) contain a much smaller core than the multimode variety. The core size for SMF is 10 microns. SMF’s smaller core only allows for a single mode of travel for the light from one end of the cable to the other. This straight-through connection allows for data to travel longer distances without a repeater than it can travel using MMF. When the light reaches the destination, the signals are then converted back into 1s and 0s and passed to the computer by the network interface card. Single mode fiber is commonly used in very long distance fiber connections, such as a backbone connection from one local area network to another. \n Fiber-Optic Cable Connectors \n \n \n \n \n Fiber cables only come in the two types discussed above: single-mode and multimode. However, the ends of each of these cables come in four varieties. \n The subscriber connector (SC) is a fiber-optic cable connector that uses a push-pull mechanism to latch into the port, similar to common audio and video cables. If you want to enable bidirectional transmission for sending and receiving data, you need to have two fiber cables, so sometimes a dual SC connector is used. \n The straight tip (ST) connector is a fiber-optic cable connector that uses a bayonet plug and socket. It was the first de facto standard connector for most commercial wiring using fiber cables and it is very commonly found in fiber networks. \n The Lucent connector (LC) is a miniaturized version of the fiber-optic SC connector. It looks somewhat like the SC, but is half the size, with a 1.25 mm ferrule instead of 2.5 mm, making it very useful when connecting multiple devices in a small area, such as on a 24-port switch’s front panel. \n The mechanical transfer-registered jack (MT-RJ) connector is a fiber-optic cable connector that is very popular for small-form-factor devices due to its small size. This connector houses two fibers and mates with locating pins on the plug. These connectors are commonly found connecting a switch to a patch panel, because both devices have a limited area on their front panels. \n \n \n', 'tags': '', 'url': 'pch11Networking Media (p.83 p.84).html'}, {'title': 'PC Software', 'text': 'https://oli.cmu.edu/jcourse/lms/students/syllabus.do?section=d87f07680a0001dc23f4f79c362d5436 \n', 'tags': '', 'url': 'PC Software.html'}, {'title': 'pcs17無線網路 (p.74~p.77)', 'text': '無線網路安全 \n \n \n 設置無線網絡時， 無線安全性 非常重要。沒有安全性，任何人都可以訪問文件和文件夾，查看所有無線傳輸， 介紹自己的惡意軟件 ，使用您的無線連接 訪問非法內容 或 通過ISP發起攻擊 或 下載有害內容 。 \n 無線網絡通過使用 無線電頻率 將 空氣 用作其 傳輸介質 。這意味著介質是不安全的，因為如果不使用加密和密碼，則 距離限制內的任何用戶都可以訪問無線網絡 。 \n 有四個簡單的步驟來保護接入點： \n 1.鎖定路由器或接入點。 \n 2.配置 服務集標識符（SSID） ，並 禁用SSID廣播 。 \n 3.配置無線安全性。 \n 4.通過 媒體訪問控制（MAC）地址限制用戶 。 \n 鎖定訪問點和訪問 \n \n \n \n \n 有幾種鎖定訪問點的方法。你 使用的方法越多，網絡將越安全。你 可以通過將默認密碼更改為強密碼來鎖定接入點或路由器。你 還可以通過 禁用無線Web訪問 來鎖定係統，以便只有直接連接的計算機才能管理該設備。你 可以 禁用遠程管理 ，以便 無法通過Internet訪問設備 。你 只能允許通過更安全的 安全超文本傳輸協議（HTTPS） 訪問。 最後，您可以 禁用通用即插即用功能 。 \n 此外，你應該通過 更改網絡的默認IP地址 來更改網絡訪問權限。 最好限制通過 動態主機配置協議（DHCP）可用的地址數量 。 您可以 更改默認的SSID ，並 禁用其廣播 ，以便用戶在連接前必須知道它是什麼。 \n \n \n 屏幕顯示可用於通用路由器設置的選項。 國家信息安全和地理空間技術聯盟（NISGTC）根據CC-BY許可使用的圖像。 \n SSID —服務集標識符 \n \n \n \n \n \n 保護無線網絡的一種方法是 禁用SSID的廣播 。 SSID或服務集標識符實質上是無線網絡的名稱。 為了保護無線網絡，您應該首先將SSID 更改為默認值以外的其他值 。 如果用戶看到默認的SSID，則通常可以假定無線訪問點上沒有管理密碼。 因此，接入點成為攻擊的目標。 另外，如果在同一區域中有多個接入點，並且它們都具有默認名稱，則很難確定哪個接入點屬於哪個網絡。 更改默認的SSID時， 請勿使用您的姓氏 ， 公司名稱或位置 ，因為這會使您的接入點成為可用於你並以你的網絡為目標的信息源。 配置完所有無線客戶端后，最好禁用SSID廣播。 這將防止訪問點宣布其在該區域中的存在。 一旦禁用了SSID廣播，用戶將無法再找到其可用網絡中顯示的無線網絡，除非他們先前已連接到該無線網絡。 這意味著即使您的客戶端計算機不廣播，也必須將其設置為連接到網絡。 \n Wi-Fi保護訪問 \n \n \n \n \n 由於Wi-Fi會通過 射頻傳輸 ，因此傳輸的數據很容易被其他任何無線電接收器查看和捕獲。 加密和網絡安全已成為各級IT專業人員最關心的問題。 如果建立了 未加密的Wi-Fi網絡 ，則它是“ 開放的 ”，附近有數據包嗅探軟件的任何人都可以捕獲主機與無線訪問點之間的傳輸。 提供開放式訪問權限的公共咖啡館和零售商這樣做是出於禮貌，但用戶必須注意，任何在線登錄信息（例如，連接到銀行，Facebook或Twitter）都不安全且容易被捕獲。 準技術人員必須了解當前的加密類型和最佳做法，以 保護WLAN 。 \n 加密類型 \n \n \n \n \n 為了提供無線網絡的安全性， 802.11標準 提供了三種主要的密碼保護/加密類型： \n 1.有線等效保密（ WEP ） \n 2.Wi-Fi保護訪問（ WPA ） \n 3.Wi-Fi保護訪問2（ WPA2 ）。 \n 有線等效保密（WEP） \n \n \n \n \n 在最初的802.11標準中，唯一提供的安全性是 WEP ，當時它聲稱與有線網絡連接一樣安全。 通過使用所有接入點和客戶端設備都將使用的 40位WEP預共享密鑰（PSK） 進行加密來保護此無線連接。 這種對稱加密是一個好主意，但是由於 密鑰太小（40位） ，攻擊者很快就將其破壞了。 \n 為了解決這個問題，WEP開始使用 64位密鑰 ，並且可以支持最 多128位的密鑰 ，這將提供更強大的加密。 不幸的是，用於加密的WEP算法還依賴於將 初始化向量（IV）與PSK結合使用來創建加密 ，並且IV僅使用24位來創建，這意味著只有16777216個可能值。 這種有限的組合值意味著IV將最終（在五到七個小時內）開始重複，並且捕獲數據包的攻擊者可以獲得具有相同IV的兩個。 這稱為密鑰流或IV攻擊。 存在許多開源實用程序，這些實用程序可以在短短幾分鐘內在現代硬件上 破解WEP密碼 。 因此，WEP是不安全的，永遠不要在您的網絡中使用。 \n Wi-Fi保護訪問（WPA） \n \n \n \n \n 電氣和電子工程師協會（IEEE）與Wi-Fi聯盟合作 ，開始開發針對WEP缺點的解決方案。 在2003年，Wi-Fi聯盟發布了 WPA標準 ，以替代目前不安全的WEP。 WPA基於相同的 Rivest Cipher 4（RC4）流密碼 構建， \xa0 但使用48位IV代替WEP的24位IV。 此升級的 IV使用臨時密鑰完整性協議（TKIP） 。 TKIP是IEEE標準，指在使用每個數據包的128位動態加密密鑰提供更安全的加密。 TKIP是一套算法， 旨在作為客戶端WLAN網絡接口卡（NIC）的固件升級，但不一定是2003年前製造的接入點。TKIP會對每個數據進行加密 帶有唯一加密密鑰的數據包 ，並且由於128位長度，該密鑰比WEP強得多。 為了增強按鍵強度，TKIP包括四個附加算法。 \n 除了TKIP，WPA標準還使用 消息完整性檢查（MIC） 來確認數據在傳輸過程中沒有被修改，這 \xa0 與WEP中使用 的 循環冗餘校驗（CRC） 相反 \xa0 。 MIC使用“ 哈希 ”來驗證消息是否未被更改。 WPA支持PSK模式和企業模式。 在企業模式下，要求用戶在交換密鑰之前進行身份驗證，並且客戶端和訪問點之間的每個密鑰只是臨時的，從而減少了洩露的機會。 不幸的是，WPA還存在著 密碼短語 和 PSK密鑰 管理方面的安全漏洞，現在也被認為是不安全的。 \n Wi-Fi保護訪問2（WPA2） \n \n \n \n \n Wi-Fi保護訪問版本2（WPA2）由於24位和48位初始化向量的不安全性而替代了WEP和WPA。 IEEE在2004年將WPA2批准為802.11i。WPA2需要使用 計數器模式密碼塊鏈接消息身份驗證代碼協議（CCMP）進行 更強的加密和完整性檢查 \xa0 。 WPA2支持預共享密鑰和較早的802.1x標準，但它指定了最安全的高級加密標準（AES）。 AES可以使用128位，192位或256位密鑰，並且與全世界以及美國政府用於保護機密網絡的算法相同。 \n 使用WPA2可以創建安全的無線網絡，但前提是要 使用良好的密碼和共享密鑰 。 WPA2還支持用於集中式用戶身份驗證的企業模式（用於公司網絡）和用於PSK支持的個人模式（用於大多數家庭和小型辦公室）。 使用WPA2進行安全保護的關鍵是強大的密碼，因為當前侵入WPA2網絡的方法是使用 \xa0 蠻力攻擊 \xa0 針對PSK。 最小密碼為8個字符，最大密碼為63個字符。 遵循強密碼協議，不使用標準詞典單詞，並且混合使用大小寫字母，數字和符號，理想的密碼長度為12-16個字符。 如果密鑰又長又復雜，攻擊者將無法穿透您的WPA2無線網絡。 \n Wi-Fi保護訪問2企業 \n \n \n \n \n WPA2企業版是使用大型企業網絡中使用的 遠程身份驗證撥入用戶服務（RADIUS）協議 的客戶端/服務器模型。 RADIUS服務器使用 UDP（用戶數據報協議） 作為傳輸方法在應用程序層中運行，通常是在 UNIX或Windows服務器 上運行的軟件後台服務。 WPA2企業消除了共享密鑰，並將其替換為用戶名和密碼以連接到公司的Wi-Fi網絡。 \n \n 屏幕顯示無線安全設置。 國家信息安全和地理空間技術聯盟（NISGTC）根據CC-BY許可使用的圖像。 \n 媒體訪問控制（MAC）過濾 \n MAC過濾是保護網絡（有線和無線）的另一種方法。MAC過濾依賴於 網絡接口卡（NIC）的第2層地址 。MAC地址是製造商分別分配給每個網絡接口卡的48位地址，前24位標識製造商，後24位標識特定的單個網絡接口卡。通過創建特定MAC地址的 白名單（允許） 或 黑名單（拒絕） ，在無線訪問點或無線路由器上配置MAC過濾。最好讓所有設備先連接到接入點，這樣它們的MAC地址就會 自動 出現在列表中，而 不必手動輸入 。請注意，不是通過MAC地址來識別人員，而是通過他們的設備來識別，因此重要的是，通過其他方式保持設備的安全。MAC過濾是整體安全解決方案的一部分，而不是其本身的解決方案。 \n \n 屏幕顯示無線路由器上的MAC過濾。 國家信息安全和地理空間技術聯盟（NISGTC）根據CC-BY許可使用的圖像。 \n 其他無線安全方法 \n \n \n \n 通過選擇靜態IP地址與動態IP地址，還可以增強無線安全性。 通過使用靜態地址，必須為子網，網關和DNS服務器手動配置每個客戶端，這對於無線網絡來說是一個更安全的選擇。 相反，可以使用動態方案，其中使用DHCP服務器自動分配地址。 儘管這可以通過使用自動配置來簡化設置，但是如果惡意用戶連接到網絡，那麼如果不採取其他步驟（例如，MAC過濾，使用WPA2 AES密碼和更改默認設置），也會自動配置他們。 \n 在小型辦公室/家庭辦公室（SOHO）網絡中，如果您有固定數量的計算機，則手動配置IP地址可能很有價值。 但是，隨著蜂窩設備和其他小型個人計算設備的普及，與使用DHCP相比，訪問網絡難以管理並且實用性大大降低。 在網絡中使用DHCP時，可以最大程度地減少可用的DHCP地址的數量，以防止惡意用戶對網絡的不必要使用。 此外，當今大多數SOHO路由器都包含一個來賓網絡，該網絡將允許用戶僅訪問您在路由器上配置的服務（通常是Internet，但不能訪問LAN）。 \n 最後，您需要牢記接入點的位置，以實現有效而安全的覆蓋。 如果使用多個接入點，則必須計劃防止這些接入點相互干擾。 這是通過使用遠距離通道在邏輯上將它們分開來防止重疊來完成的。 另外，您應確保將接入點無線電的功率電平設置得足夠低，以使其信號保持在建築物內，但又要足夠高，以在整個區域內提供完整的覆蓋範圍。 如果您的信號太強，惡意用戶可能會劫持來自停車場或馬路對面的無線信號。 這就是所謂的“ wardriving”。 \n 通過WiFi訪問網絡 \n 從Windows計算機訪問無線網絡非常簡單，但是與我們討論的許多其他功能一樣，該過程在Windows Vista和Windows 7中相似，但在Windows 8.1和Windows 10中有所不同。 \n 要訪問無線網絡，您需要兩條信息： \n \n 網絡名稱（SSID）。 \n 網絡的密碼（安全密鑰）。 \n \n \n \n Windows Vista和Windows 7 \n 在Windows Vista或Windows 7中，訪問網絡的最簡單方法是使用桌面右下角系統托盤中的Wi-Fi圖標。 \n \n Windows任務欄的屏幕快照，在系統任務欄中顯示Wi-Fi圖標。 \n \n 單擊Wi-Fi圖標將顯示可用的無線網絡列表，以及一個狀態指示器，該指示器顯示每個網絡的信號強度。 單擊您要連接的網絡的名稱。 如果看不到所需的網絡，請確保距離路由器足夠近，以便計算機可以接收無線信號。 \n \n 可用網絡列表。 \n \n 最後，輸入網絡的密碼或安全密鑰。 \n \n 輸入無線網絡密碼。 \n Windows 8.1 \n \n \n \n \n \n 在Windows 8.1中，就像在Windows Vista或Windows 7中一樣，如果您在Windows桌面中，則可以使用Wi-Fi圖標。還有另一種使用Metro界面訪問無線網絡的方法。 \n 首先，打開屏幕右側的超級按鈕菜單（或使用鍵盤命令Windows鍵（ ）+ C），然後單擊“設置”圖標。 \n \n Windows 8桌面打開了超級按鈕，顯示“設置”圖標。 \n \n 接下來，單擊“設置”菜單中顯示的Wi-Fi圖標。 \n \n 設置彈出菜單。 \n \n 單擊Wi-Fi圖標將顯示可用的無線網絡列表，以及一個狀態指示器，該指示器顯示每個網絡的信號強度。 單擊您要連接的網絡的名稱。 如果看不到所需的網絡，請確保距離路由器足夠近，以便計算機可以接收無線信號。 \n \n 可用網絡列表。 \n \n 最後，輸入網絡的密碼或安全密鑰。 \n \n 輸入無線網絡的密碼。 \n 訪問無線網絡的提示 \n \n \n \n \n \n 如果嘗試從便攜式計算機連接到無線網絡，則應確保已啟用無線卡。 某些計算機允許用戶在不使用時關閉無線卡，以節省電池電量。 在這種情況下，通常使用功能（Fn）鍵快捷方式來打開和關閉無線卡。 有關特定筆記本電腦的詳細信息，請參閱製造商的說明。 \n 機場，咖啡廳和零售商越來越有禮貌地提供免費無線訪問。 這些是開放的，不安全的網絡。 請記住，附近的任何人都容易捕獲任何在線登錄信息，例如連接到銀行，電子郵件，Facebook或Twitter。 因此，在使用免費的公共無線網絡時，除非您已通過第三方Internet安全套件或從防病毒程序添加了虛擬專用網絡（VPN），否則請不要登錄您的站點。 \n 對於經常連接的網絡，可以單擊“自動連接”框，這樣只要您在範圍內，計算機就會自動連接到網絡。 這樣可以避免您每次選擇連接時都必須選擇網絡並輸入密碼。 \n', 'tags': '', 'url': 'pcs17無線網路 (p.74~p.77).html'}, {'title': 'pcs17Wireless Networks (p.74~p.77)', 'text': 'Overview \n In this module, we will discuss wireless networks. We will focus on wireless network security and how to access a network via Wi-Fi. \n Wireless Security \n Wireless security is extremely important when setting up a wireless network. Without security, anyone can gain access to files and folders, see all wireless transmissions, introduce their own malware, use your wireless connection to access illegal content or launch an attack through your ISP, or download harmful content. \n Wireless networks use the air as their transport medium by using the radio frequencies. This means that the medium is not secure because any user within the distance limitation can access the wireless network, if encryption and passwords are not utilized. \n There are four easy steps to secure an access point: \n 1. Lock down the router or access point. \n 2. Configure the service set identifier (SSID), and disable SSID broadcasts. \n 3. Configure wireless security. \n 4. Limit users by media access control (MAC) address. \n Lock Down Access Point and Access \n There are several methods for locking down the access point. The more methods you use, the more secure the network will be. You can lock down the access point or router by changing the default password to a strong password. You can also lock down the system by disabling wireless web access so only a directly connected computer can manage the device. You can disable remote management so the device cannot be accessed over the Internet. You can only allow access through the more secure Hypertext Transfer Protocol Secure (HTTPS). Finally, you can disable universal plug-and-play. \n Additionally, you should change the network access by changing the default IP address for the network. It’s also good practice to limit the number of addresses available through the dynamic host configuration protocol (DHCP). You can change the default SSID, and disable its broadcast so users must know what it is before connecting to it. \n \n \n Caption: Screens showing options available for a generic router setup. Image used under CC-BY license from National Information Security and Geospatial Technologies Consortium (NISGTC). \n \n SSID — Service Set Identifier \n One method of securing your wireless network is to disable the broadcast of the SSID. The SSID, or service set identifier, is essentially the name of the wireless network. To secure the wireless network, you should first change the SSID to something other than the default. If a user sees a default SSID, it can often be assumed that there is no administrative password in place on the wireless access point; therefore, the access point becomes the target of attacks. Also, if there are multiple access points in the same area, and they all have the default name, it becomes difficult to determine which access point belongs to which network. When changing the default SSID, do not use your family’s name, company name, or location, as this makes your access point a source of information to use against you and target your network. Once all your wireless clients are configured, it is a good idea to disable the SSID broadcast. This will prevent the access point from announcing its presence in the area. Once the SSID is disabled from broadcasting, users will no longer find the wireless network shown in their available networks, unless they have connected to it previously. This means that you have to set your client machines to connect to the network even when it is not broadcasting. \n Wi-Fi Protected Access \n Due to the nature of Wi-Fi being transmitted through radio frequencies, the data transferred is susceptible to being viewed and captured by any other radio receiver. Encryption and network security have become a paramount concern for IT professionals at all levels. If a Wi-Fi network is set up without encryption, it is “open,” and anybody with packet sniffing software in the vicinity can capture the transmissions between the host and the wireless access point. Public cafes and retailers offering open access do so as a courtesy, but users must be aware that any online login information, such as connecting to a bank, Facebook, or Twitter, is not secure and is susceptible to capture. prospective technicians must know the current encryption types and best practices to secure a WLAN. \n Encryption Types \n In order to provide security for wireless networks, the 802.11 standards provide for three major types of password protection/encryption: wired equivalent privacy (WEP), Wi-Fi protected access (WPA), and Wi-Fi protected access 2 (WPA2). \n Wired Equivalent Privacy (WEP) \n In the original 802.11 standard, the only security provided was WEP, which at the time claimed to be as secure as a wired network connection. This wireless connection was secured using encryption with a 40-bit WEP preshared key (PSK) that all access points and client devices would use. This symmetric encryption was a good idea, but since the key was so small (40 bits), it was quickly broken by attackers. \n To solve this, WEP began using a 64-bit key, and could support keys up to 128 bits, which would provide stronger encryption. Unfortunately, the WEP algorithm used for encryption also relied on using an initialization vector (IV) in combination with the PSK to create the encryption, and the IV is created using only 24 bits, which means there are only 16,777,216 possible values. This limited combination value means that the IV will begin repeating eventually (in five to seven hours) and an attacker capturing packets can get two with the same IV. This is known as a keystream or IV attack. Many open-source utilities exist that can crack WEP passwords within just a few minutes on modern hardware. For this reason, WEP is insecure and should never be used in your networks. \n Wi-Fi Protected Access (WPA) \n The Institute for Electrical and Electronics Engineers (IEEE), in conjunction with the \xa0Wi-Fi Alliance , began developing a solution to WEP’s shortcomings. In 2003, the Wi-Fi Alliance released the WPA standard as a stopgap to replace the now insecure WEP. WPA is built around the same \xa0 Rivest Cipher 4 (RC4) stream cipher \xa0 but used a 48-bit IV in place of WEP’s 24-bit IV. This upgraded IV uses a temporal key integrity protocol (TKIP). TKIP is an IEEE standard designed to provide more secure encryption using a 128-bit dynamic per packet encryption key. TKIP is a suite of \xa0algorithms \xa0 designed as a firmware upgrade for WLAN network interface cards (NIC) on the client side, but not necessarily access points manufactured before 2003. TKIP encrypts each data \xa0packet \xa0 with a unique encryption  key , and the keys are much stronger than WEP due to the 128-bit length. To increase key strength, TKIP includes four additional algorithms. \n In addition to TKIP, the WPA standard uses message integrity check (MIC) to confirm that data was not modified in transit as opposed to the \xa0 cyclic redundancy check (CRC) \xa0 used in WEP. MIC uses a “hash” to verify that a message has not been altered. WPA supports both PSK mode and enterprise mode. In enterprise mode, users are required to authenticate before exchanging their keys and each key between the client and access point is only temporary, reducing the chance of compromise. Unfortunately, WPA also suffers security flaws centered on the use of passphrases and PSK key management, and now is also considered to be insecure. \n Wi-Fi Protected Access 2 (WPA2) \n Wi-Fi protected access version 2 (WPA2) replaces both WEP and WPA because of the insecurities with the 24-bit and 48-bit initialization vectors. IEEE ratified WPA2 as 802.11i in 2004. WPA2 requires stronger encryption and integrity checking, using \xa0 counter mode cipher block chaining message authentication code protocol (CCMP) \xa0 . While WPA2 supports a preshared key and the earlier 802.1x standards, it specifies advanced encryption standard (AES), which is the most secure. AES can use a 128, 192, or 256-bit key, and is the same algorithm used worldwide as well as by the United States government to protect classified networks. \n Using WPA2 creates a secure wireless network, but only when used with good passwords and shared keys. WPA2 also supports enterprise mode for centralized user authentication (used in corporate networks) and a personal mode for PSK support (used in most homes and small offices). The key to security with WPA2 is a strong password, since the current method of breaking into a WPA2 network is to use \xa0 brute force attacksagainst the PSK. The minimum password is eight characters and the maximum is 63 characters. The ideal password length is 12–16 characters following strong password protocol of not using standard dictionary words and using a mix of uppercase and lowercase letters, numbers, and symbols. If your key is long and complex, the attackers will not be able to penetrate your WPA2 wireless networks. For more information about securing WPA2, read this \xa0article . \n Wi-Fi Protected Access 2 Enterprise \n WPA2 enterprise is a client/server model using the remote authentication dial-in user service (RADIUS) protocol found in larger corporate networks. The RADIUS server runs in the application layer using UDP (user datagram protocol) as a transport method, and is usually a software background service running on a UNIX or Windows server. WPA2 enterprise eliminates a shared key and replaces it with a username and a password to connect to the corporate Wi-Fi network. \n \n Screen showing wireless security settings. Image used under CC-BY license from National Information Security and Geospatial Technologies Consortium (NISGTC). \n Media Access Control (MAC) Filtering \n MAC filtering is another method of securing a network (both wired and wireless). MAC filtering relies on the layer 2 address of the network interface card (NIC). A MAC address is a 48-bit address individually assigned to each network interface card by the manufacturer, with the first 24 bits identifying the manufacturer and the last 24 bits identifying the specific individual network interface card. MAC filtering is configured at the wireless access point or wireless router by creating a whitelist (allowed) or blacklist (denied) of specific MAC addresses. It is best to let all devices connect to the access point first so their MAC addresses will appear automatically in the list, and they don\'t have to be entered manually. Note that people are not identified by the MAC address, instead it is their devices that are identified, so it is important that the devices remain secure through additional means. MAC filtering is part of a total security solution, not a solution in itself. \n \n Screen displaying MAC filtering on a wireless router. Image used under CC-BY license from National Information Security and Geospatial Technologies Consortium (NISGTC). \n Additional Wireless Security Methods \n \n \n \n Wireless security can also be enhanced by choosing static versus dynamic IP addressing. By utilizing a static address, each client must manually be configured for the subnet, gateway, and DNS server, making this a more secure option for a wireless network. Conversely, a dynamic scheme could be utilized, where addresses are automatically assigned using a DHCP server. While this eases setup through the use of automatic configuration, if a malicious user connects to the network, they are also automatically configured if other steps — such as MAC filtering, use of WPA2 AES passwords, and changing default settings — are not taken. \n In a small office/home office (SOHO) network, manually configuring IP addresses might be of value, provided you have a fixed number of machines. However, with the ubiquity of cellular devices and other small personal computing devices, accessing a network is difficult to manage and much less practical than using DHCP. When using DHCP in your networks, you can minimize the number of DHCP addresses available to prevent unwanted use of your network by malicious users. Further, most SOHO routers today include a guest network that will allow users access to only services you configure at the router (usually Internet but not LAN access). \n Lastly, you need to be mindful of the placement of your access points for effective and secure coverage. If you are using more than one access point, you must plan to prevent the access points from causing interference with each other. This is done by separating them logically by using distant channels to prevent overlap. Also, you should ensure that the power levels of your access point radios are set low enough to keep their signals within your building, but high enough to provide full coverage throughout your area. If your signal is too strong, a malicious user could hijack wireless signals from the parking lot or across the street. This is known as “wardriving.” \n Accessing a Network Via WiFi \n Accessing a wireless network from a Windows computer is fairly straightforward, but as with many other features we’ve discussed, the process is similar in Windows Vista and Windows 7, but differs a bit in Windows 8.1 and Windows 10. \n To access a wireless network, you’ll need two pieces of information: \n \n The name of the network (SSID). \n The password for the network (security key). \n \n \n \n Windows Vista and Windows 7 \n From Windows Vista or Windows 7, the easiest way to access the network is by using the Wi-Fi icon in the system tray on the lower right of your Desktop. \n \n Screenshot of Windows Taskbar showing the Wi-Fi icon in the system tray. \n \n Clicking on the Wi-Fi icon brings up a list of available wireless networks, along with a status indicator showing the strength of the signal for each network. Click on the name of the network to which you would like to connect. If you don’t see your desired network, make sure that you’re close enough to the router for your computer to receive the wireless signal. \n \n List of available networks. \n \n Finally, enter the password or security key for the network. \n \n Entering the wireless network password. \n Windows 8.1 \n \n \n \n \n \n In Windows 8.1, using the Wi-Fi icon will work if you are in the Windows Desktop, just like in Windows Vista or Windows 7. There is also another way to access wireless networks using the Metro interface. \n First, open the Charms menu on the right of the screen (or use the keyboard command Windows key ( ) + C) and click on the Settings icon. \n \n Windows 8 Desktop with the Charms menu open showing the Settings icon. \n \n Next, click on the Wi-Fi icon that appears in the Settings menu. \n \n Settings pop-up menu. \n \n Clicking on the Wi-Fi icon brings up a list of available wireless networks, along with a status indicator showing the strength of the signal for each network. Click on the name of the network to which you would like to connect. If you don’t see your desired network, make sure that you’re close enough to the router for your computer to receive the wireless signal. \n \n List of available networks. \n \n Finally, enter the password or security key for the network. \n \n Entering the password for the wireless network. \n Tips for Accessing Wireless Networks \n \n \n \n \n \n If you’re trying to connect to a wireless network from a laptop computer, you should ensure that the wireless card is enabled. Some computers allow the user to turn off the wireless card when not in use to conserve battery power. Toggling the wireless card on and off in these cases is typically achieved using a function (Fn) key shortcut. See the manufacturer’s instructions for details pertaining to your specific laptop. \n Increasingly, free wireless access is offered by airports, cafes, and retailers as a courtesy. These are open, unsecured networks. Remember that any online login information, such as connecting to a bank, email, Facebook, or Twitter, is susceptible to capture by anyone nearby. Thus, care should be taken when using a free public wireless network that you do not log into your sites unless you have added a virtual private network (VPN) through a third-party Internet security suite or from your antivirus program. \n For networks that you connect to frequently, you can click the "Connect automatically" box so that your computer will automatically connect to the network whenever you are in range. This will prevent you from having to choose the network and enter the password every time you want to connect. \n \n \n \n \n', 'tags': '', 'url': 'pcs17Wireless Networks (p.74~p.77).html'}, {'title': 'pcs18有線網路安全 (p.78~p.80)', 'text': '\n \n 有線網絡比無線網絡更安全，因為您可以專門控製網絡訪問點的位置。像無線網絡一樣，有線網絡也支持MAC過濾和IP地址的靜態分配。但是，由於網絡插孔的佈線位置，有線網絡還允許您禁用未使用的端口並物理控制對網絡的訪問。 \n 保護有線網絡安全時，請考慮以下四種策略： \n 1.鎖定Internet路由器。 \n 2.控制物理安全性。 \n 3.配置靜態和動態尋址。 \n 4.通過媒體訪問控制（MAC）地址限制用戶。 \n 鎖定路由器 \n \n \n \n \n 有幾種方法可以鎖定Internet路由器。 您使用的方法越多，網絡將越安全。 您可以通過將默認密碼更改為強密碼來鎖定路由器。 您還可以通過禁用無線Web訪問來鎖定係統，以便只有直接連接的計算機才能管理該設備。 您可以禁用遠程管理，以便無法通過Internet訪問設備。 您只能允許通過更安全的超文本傳輸協議安全（HTTPS）進行訪問。 最後，您可以禁用通用即插即用功能。 \n 此外，您應該通過更改網絡的默認IP地址來更改網絡訪問權限。 最好限制通過動態主機配置協議（DHCP）可用的地址數量。 您可以更改默認服務集標識符SSID，並禁用其廣播，以便用戶在連接之前必須知道它是什麼。 \n \n 屏幕顯示Internet路由器上的MAC過濾。 \n 人身安全 \n \n \n \n \n \n 物理安全性最明顯（但有時還是被忽略）的概念是將網絡設備保持在鎖著的門後面。 您還需要注意有線網絡的物理安全性。 在較小的環境中，通常會公開看到網絡設備，例如網絡路由器，交換機甚至服務器。 如果無法鎖定設備，則可能需要考慮使用廉價的攝像頭。 \n 無線網絡允許人們從有射頻信號的任何地方進行連接。 另一方面，有線網絡要求用戶位於網絡插孔附近。 未使用的網絡插孔需要通過物理方式或通過交換機軟件進行保護。 這使網絡管理員可以控制用戶可以訪問網絡的位置。 位置應盡量減少到辦公室和安全的位置。 請勿將網絡插孔放在開放的區域，例如大廳或候機室。 但是，如果它們存在於這些位置，則可以將諸如RJ-45端口阻止程序之類的物理設備插入空插孔，以防止惡意用戶未經授權的使用。 請注意，許多RJ-45端口阻止程序都可以通過易於獲得的工具刪除， 因此，技術人員應該記住，儘管這種安全方法對機會主義攻擊相當有效，但對計劃的攻擊卻不那麼有效。 在使用受管交換機的網絡中，可以通過軟件配置端口安全性以關閉未使用的端口，或者可以使用身份驗證，以便用戶在訪問網絡服務之前必須確認自己具有網絡帳戶。 根據設備的不同，可以選擇Windows域服務器或身份驗證協議（例如802.1x）。 可以使用身份驗證或身份驗證，以便用戶在訪問網絡服務之前必須先確認自己具有網絡帳戶。 根據設備的不同，可以選擇Windows域服務器或身份驗證協議（例如802.1x）。 可以使用身份驗證或身份驗證，以便用戶在訪問網絡服務之前必須先確認自己具有網絡帳戶。 根據設備的不同，可以選擇Windows域服務器或身份驗證協議（例如802.1x）。 \n 靜態與動態尋址 \n \n \n \n \n 還可以通過選擇靜態IP地址和動態IP地址來增強有線安全性。 通過使用靜態地址，必須為子網，網關和DNS服務器手動配置每個客戶端，這對於有線網絡來說是一個更安全的選擇。 相反，可以使用動態方案，其中使用DHCP服務器自動分配地址。 儘管這可以通過使用自動配置簡化設置過程，但是如果惡意用戶連接到網絡，那麼如果不採取其他步驟（例如MAC過濾或某種類型的用戶身份驗證），也會自動配置他們。 \n 在小型辦公室/家庭辦公室（SOHO）網絡中，如果您有固定數量的計算機，則手動配置IP地址可能很有價值。 但是，隨著蜂窩設備和其他小型個人計算設備無處不在的訪問網絡，管理靜態IP變得很困難，並且比使用DHCP實用性要差得多。 在網絡中使用DHCP時，可以最大程度地減少可用的DHCP地址的數量，以防止惡意用戶對網絡的不必要使用。 此外，當今大多數SOHO路由器都包含一個來賓網絡，該網絡將允許用戶僅訪問您在路由器上配置的服務（通常是Internet，但不能訪問LAN）。 \n 媒體訪問控制（MAC）過濾 \n \n \n \n \n 與無線網絡一樣，有線網絡也支持MAC過濾。 MAC過濾是保護網絡（有線和無線）的另一種方法。 MAC過濾依賴於網絡接口卡（NIC）的第2層地址。 MAC地址是製造商分別分配給每個網絡接口卡的48位地址，前24位標識製造商，後24位標識特定的單個網絡接口卡。 通過創建特定MAC地址的白名單（允許）或黑名單（拒絕），在路由器上配置MAC過濾。 設置網絡時，最好先讓所有批准的設備連接到路由器（在啟用MAC過濾之前），這樣它們的MAC地址將自動出現在列表中，而不必手動輸入。 請注意，不能通過MAC地址來識別人員。 而是標識了它們的設備，因此，通過其他方式保持設備的安全非常重要。 MAC過濾是整體安全解決方案的一部分，而不是其本身的解決方案。 \n \n 屏幕顯示Internet路由器上的MAC過濾。 \n 通過以太網訪問網絡 \n 要訪問有線網絡，您的計算機將需要帶有RJ-45連接器的網絡接口卡（NIC）。大多數台式機都在主板上內置了NIC，許多筆記本電腦也是如此。但是，隨著無線網絡訪問變得越來越普遍，一些新型筆記本電腦放棄了有線NIC，轉而使用無線NIC，以使筆記本電腦更薄，更輕。您還需要網絡電纜（也稱為以太網電纜），以及連接到網絡的方式（路由器，交換機或集線器）。 \n 設置有線網絡連接通常非常容易-通常，將網絡電纜插入網絡接口卡後，操作系統會自動創建有線網絡連接。 與無線網絡一樣，有線網絡通常使用動態主機配置協議（DHCP）配置適當的IP地址。 \n 要配置有線網絡連接，請單擊Windows桌面上系統托盤中的網絡圖標。 這將啟動一個彈出窗口，告訴您網絡連接的名稱，並提供指向“控制面板”小程序的鏈接：Windows網絡和共享中心。 \n \n \xa0 \xa0 \xa0 \xa0 \xa0 \xa0 \xa0 \xa0 \xa0 系統托盤中的網絡連接狀態。 \n \n 單擊“打開網絡和共享中心”將帶您進入“網絡和共享中心”控制面板，您可以在其中設置新的網絡連接，配置家庭組和共享選項或對網絡連接問題進行故障排除。 \n \n 網絡和共享中心控制面板。 \n \n 要查看有關當前網絡連接的詳細信息，請單擊“本地連接”。 這將打開一個窗口，該窗口提供有關網絡連接狀態的信息。 例如，在下面的圖像中，我們可以看到我們有一個IPv4連接，已經連接了大約6分鐘，並且速度為100 Mbps。 \n \n \xa0 \xa0 \xa0 \xa0 \xa0 \xa0 \xa0 \xa0 \xa0 \xa0 \xa0 \xa0 \xa0 \xa0 \xa0 本地連接狀態窗口。 \n \n 單擊“詳細信息”按鈕可提供有關網絡連接的更多信息。 在這裡，我們可以看到網卡是Realtek PCIe卡，其MAC地址為00：21：85：4D：14：22。 我們目前的IP地址為192.168.1.33。 我們的路由器（用作默認網關，DHCP服務器和DNS服務器）位於192.168.1.1。 \n \n \xa0 \xa0 \xa0 \xa0 \xa0 \xa0 \xa0 \xa0 \xa0 \xa0 \xa0 \xa0 \xa0 \xa0網絡連接詳細信息窗口。 \n \n 返回到“本地連接”窗口，如果單擊“屬性”，我們將看到可以配置的選項列表。 \n \n \xa0 \xa0 \xa0 \xa0 \xa0 \xa0 \xa0 \xa0 \xa0 \xa0 \xa0 \xa0 \xa0 \xa0 \xa0 本地連接屬性窗口。 \n \n 我們在這裡選擇的最常見的配置選項是Internet協議版本4（TCP / IPv4）。 單擊此將打開一個窗口，其中顯示了我們當前的TCP / IP配置： \n \n \xa0 \xa0 \xa0 \xa0 \xa0 \xa0 \xa0 \xa0 \xa0 \xa0 \xa0 \xa0 \xa0 \xa0 \xa0 \xa0 \xa0 TCP / IP屬性窗口。 \n \n 在這裡我們可以看到我們當前的連接正在使用DHCP，因為它被設置為自動獲取IP地址和DNS服務器地址。 如果要更改為使用靜態IP地址，請單擊標有“使用以下IP地址”的單選按鈕，然後輸入我們的靜態IP地址。 當使用靜態IP地址時，我們還必須指定希望使用的子網掩碼和默認網關。 對於家庭網絡，子網掩碼通常為255.255.255.0，默認網關是路由器的IP地址（在這種情況下為192.168.1.1）。 \n 同樣，我們可以根據需要指定DNS服務器地址，而不是從路由器自動獲取DNS服務器地址。 為此，我們將單擊標記為“使用以下DNS服務器地址”的單選按鈕，然後輸入我們要使用的主要（首選）和輔助（備用）DNS服務器的IP地址。 \n \n \n \n', 'tags': '', 'url': 'pcs18有線網路安全 (p.78~p.80).html'}, {'title': 'pcs18Wired Network Security (p.78~p.80)', 'text': "Overview \n In this module, we will discuss wired networks. We will focus on wired network security and how to access a network via Ethernet. \n Wired networks are more secure than wireless networks because you can control specifically where the network access points are located. Wired networks, like wireless networks, support MAC filtering and static assignment of IP addresses. But, wired networks also allow you to disable unused ports and physically control access to the network due to the wiring location of the network jacks. \n Here are four tactics to consider when securing a wired network: \n 1. Lock down the Internet router. \n 2. Control physical security. \n 3. Configure static vs. dynamic addressing. \n 4. Limit users by media access control (MAC) address. \n Lock Down Router \n \n \n There are several methods for locking down the Internet router. The more methods you use, the more secure the network will be. You can lock down the router by changing the default password to a strong password. You can also lock down the system by disabling wireless web access so only a directly connected computer can manage the device. You can disable remote management so the device cannot be accessed over the Internet. You can only allow access through the more secure hypertext transfer protocol secure (HTTPS). Finally, you can disable universal plug-and-play. \n Additionally, you should change the network access by changing the default IP address for the network. It’s also good practice to limit the number of addresses available through the dynamic host configuration protocol (DHCP). You can change the default service set identifier SSID, and disable its broadcast so users must know what it is before connecting to it. \n \n Screen displaying MAC filtering on an Internet router. \n Physical Security \n The most obvious (and yet sometimes overlooked) concept of physical security is to keep networking equipment behind a locked door. You also need to be mindful of the physical security of your wired network. In smaller environments, it is commonplace to see network equipment such as the network router, switches or even servers out in the open. If keeping your equipment locked is not an option, an inexpensive camera setup might be a consideration. \n \n \n \n \n \n Wireless networks allow a person to connect from wherever there is a radio frequency signal. Wired networks, on the other hand, require the user to be located close to a network jack. Unused network jacks need to be secured either physically or through the switch software. This allows the network administrator to control the locations where users can access the network. Locations should be minimized to offices and secure locations. Network jacks should never be left in open areas, such as lobbies or waiting rooms. However, if they are present in those locations, a physical device such as an RJ-45 port-blocker can be inserted into the empty jack, preventing unauthorized usage by malicious users. Note that many RJ-45 port-blockers can be removed with tools that are easy to obtain, so technicians should keep in mind that while this security method is fairly effective against opportunistic attacks, it is not as effective against planned attacks. In a network using managed switches, port security can be configured through the software to shut down unused ports, or authentication can be used so that users must confirm they have a network account prior to gaining access to network services. A Windows domain server or an authentication protocol such as 802.1x are options, depending on the equipment. \n Static Vs. Dynamic Addressing \n \n \n \n \n Wired security can also be enhanced by choosing static versus dynamic IP addressing. By utilizing a static address, each client must manually be configured for the subnet, gateway, and DNS server, making this a more secure option for a wired network. Conversely, a dynamic scheme can be utilized, where addresses are automatically assigned using a DHCP server. While this eases setup through the use of automatic configuration, if a malicious user connects to the network, they are also automatically configured if other steps — such as MAC filtering or some type of user authentication — are not taken. \n In a small office/home office (SOHO) network, manually configuring IP addresses might be of value, provided you have a fixed number of machines. However, with the ubiquity of cellular devices and other small personal computing devices accessing the network, it is difficult to manage static IPs and much less practical than using DHCP. When using DHCP in your networks, you can minimize the number of DHCP addresses available to prevent unwanted use of your network by malicious users. Further, most SOHO routers today include a guest network that will allow users access to only services you configure at the router (usually Internet but not LAN access). \n Media Access Control (MAC) Filtering \n \n \n \n \n Note: Some of the text in this section is used under CC-BY license from the \xa0 National Information Security and Geospatial Technologies Consortium (NISGTC). \n Just as in wireless networks, wired networks support MAC filtering. MAC filtering is another method of securing a network (both wired and wireless). MAC filtering relies on the layer 2 address of the network interface card (NIC). A MAC address is a 48-bit address individually assigned to each network interface card by the manufacturer, with the first 24 bits identifying the manufacturer and the last 24 bits identifying the specific individual network interface card. MAC filtering is configured at the router by creating a whitelist (allowed) or blacklist (denied) of specific MAC addresses. When setting up a network, it is best to let all approved devices connect to the router first (before enabling MAC filtering) so their MAC addresses will appear automatically in the list, and they don't have to be entered manually. Note that people are not identified by the MAC address; instead, it is their devices that are identified, so it is important that the devices remain secure through additional means. MAC filtering is part of a total security solution, not a solution in itself. \n \n Screen displaying MAC filtering on an Internet router. \n Network Access Via Ethernet \n To access a wired network, your computer will need a network interface card (NIC) with an RJ-45 connector. Most desktop computers come with an NIC built into the motherboard, and many laptops do as well. However, with wireless network access becoming increasingly common, some newer laptops forgo the wired NIC in favor of a wireless NIC in order to keep the laptop thinner and lighter. You also need a network cable (also called an Ethernet cable), and a way to connect to the network (router, switch, or hub). \n Setting up a wired network connection is usually fairly easy — typically wired network connections are automatically created by the operating system once a network cable is plugged into the network interface card. As with wireless networks, wired networks often use dynamic host configuration protocol (DHCP) to configure the proper IP addresses. \n To configure a wired network connection, click on the network icon in the system tray on the Windows desktop. This will launch a pop-up window that tells you the name of the network connection, and also provides a link to the Control Panel applet: the Windows Network and Sharing Center. \n \n Network connection status from the system tray. \n \n Clicking on Open Network and Sharing Center takes you to the Network and Sharing Center control panel, where you can set up a new network connection, configure homegroup and sharing options, or troubleshoot problems with the network connection. \n \n Network and Sharing Center control panel. \n \n To see details about the current network connection, click on Local Area Connection. This brings up a window that gives information on the status of the network connection. For example, in the image below, we can see that we have an IPv4 connection, we’ve been connected for about six minutes, and we have a speed of 100 Mbps. \n \n Local Area Connection Status window. \n \n Clicking on the Details button provides even more information about the network connection. Here we can see that the network card is a Realtek PCIe card with a MAC address of 00:21:85:4D:14:22. We currently have an IP address of 192.168.1.33. Our router (which is serving as Default Gateway, DHCP Server, and DNS Server) is at 192.168.1.1. \n \n Network Connection Details window. \n \n Going back to the Local Area Connection window, if we click on Properties, we can see a list of options that we can configure. \n \n Local Area Connection Properties window. \n \n The most common configuration option that we would choose here will be Internet Protocol Version 4 (TCP/IPv4). Clicking on this brings up a window that shows our current TCP/IP configuration: \n \n TCP/IP Properties window. \n \n Here we can see that our current connection is using DHCP because it is set to obtain an IP address and DNS server address automatically. If we want to change this to use a static IP address, we would click the radio button labeled “Use the following IP address” and enter our static IP address. When using a static IP address, we must also specify the subnet mask and default gateway we wish to use. The subnet mask is typically 255.255.255.0 for a home network, and the default gateway is the IP address for the router (in this case, 192.168.1.1). \n Similarly, we can specify DNS server addresses if we wish, rather than obtaining DNS server addresses automatically from the router. To do so, we would click the radio button labeled “Use the following DNS server addresses” and enter the IP addresses for the primary (preferred) and secondary (alternate) DNS servers we would like to use. \n \n \n \n", 'tags': '', 'url': 'pcs18Wired Network Security (p.78~p.80).html'}, {'title': 'pcs19惡意軟件 (p.81~p.85)', 'text': '\n \n 惡意軟件是一個廣泛泛指旨在禁用或破壞計算機和網絡的所有類型的惡意代碼的術語。病毒，蠕蟲，特洛伊木馬，間諜軟件和廣告軟件都是不同類型的惡意軟件。病毒是影響計算機運行方式的計算機程序。病毒可以執行和復制。病毒需要主機文件才能傳播。蠕蟲是可以在沒有主機文件的情況下進行複制並且可以在系統之間移動的惡意代碼。特洛伊木馬，也簡稱為特洛伊木馬，是構成為合法文件的惡意代碼文件。它不能執行或複制自身。通過偽裝成合法文件（例如電子郵件附件），它會欺騙用戶打開文件並在不知不覺中執行惡意代碼。攻擊者經常使用木馬來破壞或竊取數據。 \n 間諜軟件是惡意代碼，未經您的同意，它會獲取有關您的數據和計算機活動的信息。它可以收集個人信息，還可以更改計算機的配置。一些用戶會同意在下載應用程序時通過同意條款和條件來跟踪數據和使用情況的軟件。如果用戶同意進行此類跟踪，則通常不將軟件程序視為間諜軟件。 \n 廣告軟件是顯示不需要的廣告的軟件。有時，該軟件會阻止用戶關閉彈出廣告窗口。廣告軟件還可以將用戶從預期網站重定向到廣告網站。 \n 惡意軟件症狀 \n \n \n \n \n 惡意軟件既容易檢測又很難檢測。 如果您已安裝了良好的防病毒軟件並且經常進行系統掃描，則防病毒軟件應保護您免受任何已知威脅的威脅，並在將未知威脅添加到特徵庫後對其進行檢測。 您的計算機本身還會通過顯示某些症狀來告訴您何時可能存在惡意軟件。 \n 例如，如果您的Web瀏覽器開始訪問奇怪的站點或者您遇到Internet連接問題，則病毒，蠕蟲或特洛伊木馬可能已經感染了您的計算機。 發生這種情況的原因是，許多類型的惡意軟件都會通過修改DNS服務器地址或網關地址或在系統上安裝Web代理來破壞Internet連接。 對Web代理的更改可能導致您的所有Internet通信都通過攻擊者的系統進行路由，從而增加了連接到網絡時的延遲。 同樣，許多病毒和蠕蟲會阻止系統更新的發生，從而導致它們失敗。 這可以防止攻擊者實施漏洞修復程序，從而使攻擊者可以在系統上保持更長的時間，因為這些漏洞與攻擊者可能用來獲取對系統的訪問權限相同。 惡意軟件rootkit允許對計算機的高層訪問，並隱藏其存在或其他惡意軟件的存在。 rootkit的症狀包括重命名的系統文件，對文件權限的更改以及目錄中丟失的文件。 間諜軟件和廣告軟件通常會導致用戶在Web瀏覽期間出現多個彈出窗口。 \n 總體而言，間諜軟件和其他惡意軟件會降低計算機性能，因為計算機必須同時處理應用程序和後台惡意軟件的工作量，從而感染計算機並搶走系統處理資源。 您還可以通過使用netstat之類的工具查看網絡連接來確定計算機是否與未知服務器通信，從而確定計算機是否感染了惡意軟件。 最後，如果您收到大量不需要的電子郵件，則可能是垃圾郵件的受害者。 \n 隔離 \n 當您的計算機感染了惡意軟件時，最佳實踐是從網絡中刪除計算機並隔離受感染的文件。通過從網絡中刪除計算機，可以防止感染傳播到網絡中的其他計算機。通常，攻擊者將諸如病毒之類的惡意軟件作為其攻擊的第一枝，一旦獲得對您工作站的初始訪問權，他們就將其用作登台點，以進一步擴展對網絡中其他計算機的訪問。 \n 許多公司製定了隔離策略，以通過刪除受感染的計算機來保護網絡的其餘部分免受攻擊，而其他公司則可以將受感染的主機留在網絡上，但從邏輯上將其隔離在防火牆或其他虛擬LAN連接之後。 這允許計算機保持連接到網絡，以便監視攻擊者的方法，同時仍將其與網絡的其餘部分保護起來。 組織的信息安全團隊將根據組織的策略，建議是否從網絡中斷開受感染計算機的連接。 \n 在家庭或小型企業環境中，始終最好的做法是通過物理斷開以太網電纜的連接並關閉所有無線NIC（如果有）來從網絡上刪除受感染的工作站。 防病毒軟件隔離了受感染的文件後，您應在將工作站返回網絡之前修復引起感染的問題。 \n 修復系統的步驟 \n \n \n 儘管受感染的系統可能會成為噩夢，但是您可以採取一些步驟來將系統邏輯上還原到最佳狀態。 首先，您需要根據我們之前描述的症狀來識別正在發生的事情。 一旦確定，就可以開始隔離文件或系統，以防止感染蔓延。 如果它是一個被感染的文件，則大多數防病毒軟件可以在重新啟動進入“安全模式”並運行完整病毒掃描後刪除感染。 但是，最佳做法是，首先禁用操作系統的“系統還原”功能，然後重新啟動進入安全模式，然後完成修復。 這樣可以防止病毒在系統還原點中連續備份。 \n \n \xa0 \xa0 \xa0系統保護窗口。 圖片由Jason Dion 根據CC-BY許可使用 。 \n \n 無論您如何修復系統，在感染後始終要安裝和/或更新防病毒軟件。 始終確保將其配置為自動掃描和更新，以防止將來被感染。 完成此操作後，您可以在操作系統中重新啟用系統還原功能並創建新的還原點。 確保正確標記此還原點，例如“病毒清除後”，以便您記住其含義。 \n 安裝或更新防病毒軟件後，需要重新啟用系統還原。 要啟用系統還原，您需要訪問其菜單選項。 首先，右鍵單擊我的計算機，然後選擇屬性。 接下來，從左側菜單欄中選擇系統保護。 接下來，單擊系統保護選項卡。 在這裡，您可以單擊系統還原以還原到先前的還原點，也可以單擊創建以創建新的還原點。 要啟用或禁用此功能，請單擊配置進行配置設置。 \n \n \xa0 \xa0 \xa0 \xa0 \xa0系統屬性窗口。 圖片由Jason Dion 根據CC-BY許可使用 。 \n \n 觀看以下視頻，了解有關惡意軟件清除的最佳做法： \n \n \n 教育最終目標 \n 在當今的現代計算機時代，一盎司的預防勝過一磅的治療仍然是正確的。保護您的網絡和防止惡意軟件感染的最有效方法之一是確保您的用戶正在接受適當的網絡安全教育。預防攻擊和感染將為您節省大量時間和資源，否則將需要花費大量時間來排除感染。 \n 對用戶進行培訓，使其在工作和家庭中都能保持最新的反惡意軟件（例如防病毒和反間諜軟件）的方法。 用戶需要了解如何掃描其係統中是否存在惡意軟件，以及如何配置其應用程序以進行自動掃描。 也需要對各種惡意軟件類型/技術有基本的了解，以便用戶可以識別受感染系統的症狀。 每個人都應該掃描可移動媒體以查找惡意軟件，並防止在其係統上發生自動運行，因為這是攻擊者的常見入侵媒介。 如果計算機被感染，用戶應了解您組織的策略，即如何應對惡意軟件威脅，如何隔離可疑文件以及如何防止感染蔓延。 \n 此外，良好的反網絡釣魚教育至關重要，因為這是當今正在發生的高級持續威脅（APT）的最常見媒介之一。 反網絡釣魚教育將有助於防止用戶進行社交工程，以使其不知不覺地打開了攻擊門的大門，例如單擊可疑電子郵件所附的特洛伊木馬。 \n', 'tags': '', 'url': 'pcs19惡意軟件 (p.81~p.85).html'}, {'title': 'pcs19Malware (p.81~p.85)', 'text': '\n \n Overview \n In this module, we will discuss malware. We will cover symptoms of malware, along with different ways to troubleshoot malware problems. It is important to understand the different types of malware. \n Malware is a term that broadly refers to all types of malicious code that are designed to disable or damage computers and networks. Viruses, worms, Trojans, spyware, and adware are all different types of malware. A virus is a computer program that impacts how the computer operates. A virus can both execute and replicate itself. A virus needs a host file to spread. A worm is malicious code that can replicate without a host file and can move from system to system. A Trojan horse, also referred to simply as a Trojan, is a file of malicious code that poses as a legitimate file. It can not execute or replicate itself. By posing as a legitimate file, such as an attachment to an email, it tricks the user into opening the file and unknowingly executing the malicious code. Attackers often use Trojans to damage or steal data. \n Spyware is malicious code that, without your consent, obtains information about your data and your computer activity. It can collect personal information and can also change your computer’s configuration. Some users will consent to software that tracks data and usage by agreeing to the terms and conditions when downloading an app. If the user consents to such tracking, the software program is usually not considered spyware. \n Adware is software that displays unwanted advertisements. Sometimes, the software will prevent the user from closing the pop-up ad window. Adware may also redirect the user from the intended website to an advertising website. \n Malware Symptoms \n \n \n \n \n Malware can be both easy and difficult to detect. If you have good antivirus software installed and are doing system scans often, your antivirus software should protect you from any known threats, and detect unknown threats once they are added to the signature database. Your computer itself will also tell you when malware may be present, by showing certain symptoms. \n For example, a virus, worm, or Trojan may have infected your machine if your web browser begins to access strange sites or you experience Internet connectivity issues. This occurs because many types of malware corrupt Internet connectivity by modifying your DNS server address or gateway address, or installing a web proxy on your system. The change to a web proxy can cause all your Internet traffic to be routed through the attacker’s system, increasing latency when connecting to the network. Also, many viruses and worms prevent system updates from occurring, causing them to fail. This allows the attacker to maintain a presence on your system longer by preventing bug fixes from being implemented, since those are the same bugs the attacker may use to gain access to your system. A malware rootkit allows high-level access to your computer and hides its presence, or the presence of other malware. Symptoms of rootkits include renamed system files, changes to file permissions, and missing files in your directories. Spyware and adware often result in the user having multiple pop-ups appear during web browsing. \n Overall, spyware and other malware will slow your computer performance because the computer has to process both your applications and the workload of the background malware infecting your computer and robbing it of system processing resources. You can also tell if your computer is infected with malware by looking at your network connections using a tool such as netstat to determine if your computer is communicating with unknown servers. Finally, if you are receiving a large amount of unwanted emails, you may be a victim of spam. \n Quarantine \n When your machine is infected with malware, the best practice is to remove the computer from the network and quarantine the infected files. By removing the computer from the network, you are preventing the spread of the infection to the other machines in your network. Often, attackers use malware such as viruses as the first prong in their attack, and once they gain initial access to your workstation, they use it as a staging point to further expand their access to other machines across the network. \n Many companies have instituted a quarantine policy to protect the rest of their network from attacks by removing the infected machines, while others may leave an infected host on the network, but logically quarantine it behind a firewall or other virtual LAN connection. This allows the machine to remain connected to the network in order to monitor the attacker’s methodology, while still securing it from the rest of the network. Your organization’s information security team will advise whether or not to disconnect an infected machine from the network, based on your organization’s policies. \n In a home or small business environment, it is always best practice to remove the infected workstation from the network by physically disconnecting the Ethernet cable and turning off any wireless NICs if they are present. Once your antivirus software quarantines the infected files, you should then remediate the issues that caused the infection before returning the workstation to your network. \n Steps to Remediating the System \n \n \n While an infected system can become a nightm \n are, there are steps you can take to logically restore the system back to an optimal state. First, you need to identify what is occurring based on the symptoms we described earlier. Once identified, you can begin to quarantine the files or system to prevent spread of the infection. If it is a single file that is infected, most antivirus software can remove the infection if you reboot into “safe mode” and run a full virus scan. It is a best practice, though, to first disable the “system restore” feature of your operating system, then reboot into safe mode, and complete the remediation. This will prevent the virus from being continually backed up in your system restore points. \n \n System protection window. Image used under CC-BY license from\xa0Jason Dion. \n \n Regardless of how you remediated the system, always install and/or update your antivirus after infection. Always ensure it is configured for automated scanning and updates to prevent future infection. Once this is complete, then you can re-enable the system restore feature in your operating system and create a new restore point. Ensure you label this restore point properly, such as “after virus cleanup,” so you will remember what it means. \n After you have installed or updated your antivirus software, you need to reenable system restore. To enable system restore, you need to access its menu options. First, right-click on my computer and select properties. Next, from the left menu bar, select system protection. Next, click on system protection tab. From here, you can click on system restore to restore to a previous restore point, or click on create to create a new restore point. To enable or disable this feature, click on configure for configuration settings. \n \n System properties window. Image used under CC-BY license from \xa0 Jason Dion . \n \n Watch the following video to learn about best practices in malware removal: \n \n \n \n Educating End Users \n \n The adage an ounce of prevention is worth a pound of cure is still true in this modern computer age. One of the most effective methods of protecting your network and preventing malware infection is to ensure your users are receiving appropriate cybersecurity education. Preventing attacks and infections will save you a good deal of time and resources that would otherwise have to be spent troubleshooting an infection. \n Train your users on methods to keep anti-malware software (like antivirus and antispyware) up to date both at work and at home. Users needs to understand how to scan their systems for malware and configure their applications for automatic scanning. A basic understanding of the various malware types/techniques is also necessary, so a user can identify the symptoms of an infected system. Everyone should scan removable media for malware and prevent auto-run from occurring on their systems, as this is a common intrusion vector for attackers. If a computer becomes infected, users should be aware of your organization’s policy on how to respond to malware threats, how to quarantine suspected files, and how to prevent the spread of the infection. \n Additionally, a good anti-phishing education is essential, as this is one of the most common vectors of advanced persistent threats (APTs) that are occurring today. Anti-phishing education will help prevent users from being socially engineered to unwittingly opening the door to an attack, such as clicking on a Trojan attached to a suspicious email. \n \n \n \n \n \n', 'tags': '', 'url': 'pcs19Malware (p.81~p.85).html'}]};